<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada, US to Set Salmon Fishing Limits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Canada and the United States will
have a salmon fishing season this year again without agreement,
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
"Hopes for a negotiated settlement and cooperative management of
the North Pacific salmon fishery are effectively dead this year," said
Canada's leading newspaper the Globe and Mail.
</P>
<P>
Canada and the U.S. has held rounds of talks without reaching any
agreement. The United States sent a last-minute counterproposal to
Canada's final concessions Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is virtually certain to be rejected soon because it revisits
scientific issues on which Canada has already taken a firm stand," the
paper reported.
</P>
<P>
"Science is not the issue," a senior advisor to the Canadian
government was quoted as saying. "We've been through those issues for
months and months."
</P>
<P>
By this weekend, Canada is likely to announce this season's fishing
plan for the Canadian fleet, in a manner which offers no cooperation
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Canada will allow its fishermen to intercept the maximum U.S.-bound
fish possible, subject only to constraints for conservation purposes.
</P>
<P>
And the United States plans to allow its fishermen to intercept
even more Canadian-bound Fraser River sockeye than it was asking in
talks which broke down last Friday, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Fisheries Minister David Anderson has said that Canada is
ready to go ahead and fish salmon without reaching an agreement with
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"We have done that for the last four years, gone into a fishing
season without agreements with the Americans. It's possible to do,"
the minister was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
