<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Wants Step-by-Step Prohibition of Landmines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China is not opposed to a phased
ban on anti-personnel landmines (APL), but cannot agree to any
immediate total ban, China's ambassador to the Conference on
Disarmament Sha Zukang said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the last meeting of this year's second session of
the U.N.-sponsored talks, Sha said, "In order to meet its
legitimate territorial defense requirements, China cannot but
reserve its legitimate right to use APLs on its own territory
before alternative means are found and defensive capabilities
established.
</P>
<P>
"China can only accept an international APL agreement that fully
accommodates its above-mentioned security concerns," Sha said in
his speech.
</P>
<P>
"China has always pursued an independent foreign policy of peace
and never engages in overseas aggression," Sha said. "We have no
intention of using landmines in other countries.
</P>
<P>
"Should China use APLs under legitimate circumstances, it would
be for the purpose of defending itself against foreign military
intervention or aggression, safeguarding its national unification
and territorial integrity and ensuring a peaceful life for its own
people."
</P>
<P>
The conference today decided to appoint a special coordinator to
look into launching talks to ban the use, storage, production and
transfer of landmines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
