<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Inflation to Remain Low this Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Inflation in Canada will remain at
the low end of the Bank of Canada's target range of 1 to 3 percent
for the rest of the year, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Thiessen, governor of the central bank, said Canada's
inflation would remain low because there is still slack in the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Recent data showed the rate of economic expansion in Canada had
accelerated since the beginning of the year, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
The increased demand came from households and was concentrated
on interest-rate sensitive items such as housing and consumer
durables.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian industry is in a strong competitive position, and
foreign demand for Canadian goods and services would remain an
important contributor to the expanding economy, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In addition, business demand also continued strong with
increased investment in capital goods.
</P>
<P>
Canada's core rate of inflation, excluding food, energy and
indirect taxes, was 1.7 percent in March, compared with a peak of
1.8 percent in December last year.
</P>
<P>
There is still an output gap representing slack in the economy
and this will help keep inflationary pressures in the lower half
of the bank's target range, the governor noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
