<HEADLINE> Albright Arrives in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright arrived here this evening for a two-day visit to Vietnam
to boost diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministry sources said that Vietnamese Foreign Minister
Nguyen Manh Cam and Albright will hold talks on Friday
morning. Albright is also scheduled to meet Vietnamese Prime
Minister Vo Van Kiet in Hanoi and the top leader of the Communist
Party, Do Muoi, in Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
Albright is the second U.S. secretary of state to visit Vietnam
since the U.S. and Vietnam normalized diplomatic relations in July
1995.
</P>
<P>
During Albright's stay in Hanoi, Vietnam and the U.S. are
likely to sign an agreement on copyright, diplomatic sources here
said.
</P>
<P>
She will also explore progress in accounting for
U.S. servicemen who went missing in the Vietnam War, a key issue
in bilateral ties, State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said.
</P>
<P>
Albright will also discuss economic relations and broader
political issues with Vietnamese officials, Burns added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
