<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Rejects Line-Item Veto Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of the United
States has turned down a challenge against the presidential
line-item veto in a 7-2 decision Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The law, which was to go into effect earlier this year before
the court challenge, gives the president the power to veto
individual appropriations and limited tax loopholes instead of
having to veto an entire bill.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, U.S. District Judge Thomas Jackson ruled the law
was unconstitutional because it tried to allow Congress to
transfer legislative power to the president.
</P>
<P>
The suit challenging the line-item veto was filed in January by
five Democrats and a retired Republican Senator.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton and the Justice Department had
urged Jackson to uphold the law, then the administration appealed
directly to the Supreme Court.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
