<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Maltreatment of American </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government today
denied any maltreatment of a black American who was arrested
eight months ago on charge of unlawful entry into the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the state-run official news agency IRNA, the
Iranian representative mission at the United Nations in its
statement "outrightly rejected the maltreatment of an American"
and termed it as "part of the Clinton administration's
propaganda against Iran."
</P>
<P>
Tehran issued the statement in a response to the accusation by
U.S. State Department spokesman John Dinger Wednesday against
Iranian officials for maltreating American citizen.
</P>
<P>
A black American man named Joseph Morris has been in
detention in an Iranian prison for eight months for unlawful
entry into the country.
</P>
<P>
The arrest was revealed by Iran's Judiciary Chief Ayatollah
Mohammad Yazdi at a press conference here on June 24.
</P>
<P>
An aide to the judiciary chief said "the gentleman, a black
Muslim, was caught in Ahvaz eight month ago. He has been in
detention since then."
</P>
<P>
Dinger said that American citizens visiting Iran were badly
treated by Iranian officials. "The State Department had
forewarned U.S. citizens of detention and harassment by Iranian
officials," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian statement said that these remarks are another
example of the malevolent U.S. propaganda against Iran.
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed that those individuals who illegally
enter Iran are regarded as violators and like any other sovereign
nation, Iran reserves the right of prosecuting a violator
according to the defined laws of the country.
</P>
<P>
More than once, the U.S. citizen who is detained for illegal
entry into Iran has met officials of the Swiss consulate in
Tehran which takes care of American interests in Iran, the
statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
