<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   China's Disarmament Ambassador on Anti-Personnel Landmines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China's Ambassador for Disarmament
Affairs Sha Zukang today appealed to developed countries to make
greater efforts to help clear anti-personnel landmines (APL) left
over from past conflicts so that local people affected by the
mines could lead normal lives.
</P>
<P>
He said the clearance of abandoned landmines should become an
important element in resolving the APL issue, both from the point
of view of humanitarian concerns and of the fulfillment of arms
control obligations.
</P>
<P>
Sha was speaking at the last meeting of the current session of
the Conference on Disarmement in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided to appoint a coordinator to look into
launching talks on banning the use, storage, production and
transfer of landmines.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The most pressing issue facing the international
community is the early elimination of civilian casualties caused
by landmines.
</P>
<P>
"Almost all such casualties have been caused by those landmines
already deployed. So long as these landmines remain uncleared,
people living in landmine-affected places cannot enjoy
tranquility, let alone a peaceful life and economic
reconstruction."
</P>
<P>
Sha said he hoped all capable countries, especially those
developed countries with better financial resources technologies
and equipment, would make even greater efforts to help removing
landmines left over from past conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Talking about landmines on the territories of some countries
deployed or abandoned by foreign troops, Sha said, "These countries
concerned have requested the mine-deploying countries to shoulder the
responsibility of removing those landmines."
</P>
<P>
Sha said measures should also be taken to prevent the
indiscriminate use of landmines, especially the old-type dumb
mines. "Only in this way can we resolve the landmine issue once
and for all." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
