<HEADLINE> EDs: Repeat With Date Correction hke -- Waigel Says Tax Reform Vital for German Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
said today that the government's planned tax reform would help
boost the economy, employment and flagging foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The 1998-99 tax reform plan involves cutting mainly income and
corporate tax levels, with total net tax cuts reaching 30 billion
marks (17.4 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"The negative image of Germany as a high-tax country will
become invalid," Waigel told the Bundestag, the lower house of
parliament dominated by Chancellor Helmut Kohl's center-right
coalition, which is expected to pass the tax bill today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bill would close a series of complex tax
loopholes to raise funds.
</P>
<P>
Waigel said the tax reform plan would boost economic growth,
help reduce Germany's record unemployment which is now over 11
percent and reverse the fall in foreign investment over the last
few years.
</P>
<P>
After being approved by the Bundestag, the bill will go to the
Bundesrat, the upper house, which is controlled by the main
opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD). The SPD has vowed to
veto the reform plan.
</P>
<P>
Its finance expert Ingrid Matthaeus-Maier described as "crazy"
the government's plan to reduce the top marginal income tax rate
to 39 percent from the present 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
If the veto succeeds, the bill will be sent to a mediating
committee consisting of government and opposition members to
negotiate a compromise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
