<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Opposition Defends Lenin Mausoleum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of Russian left-wing
oppositions today expressed their determination to prevent the
reburial of Lenin's body and to defend the Lenin's Mausoleum in
Red Square, according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference at the editorial office of the newspaper
"Pravda" the leaders of the recently formed "Lenin Defense
Committee" unanimously agreed that the reburial of Lenin's body
and removal of the Mausoleum from the Red Square would mean "a
step towards civil war".
</P>
<P>
A statement distributed at the press conference warns that "the
wrath of the people could erupt into unpredictable forms and
dimensions if this dark plan was carried out."
</P>
<P>
These opposition leaders said in the document "We declare that
we shall resort to all the available ways and means to resist it,
ranging from the publication of leaflets to direct confrontation."
</P>
<P>
The "Lenin Defense Committee" consists of leaders of most of
the Russian parties and organizations of communist hue and of
"left-patriotic" orientation, include leaders of the "Labour
Russia" -- Viktor Anpilov, the Russian Communist Party-CPSU --
Alexei Prigarin, the Russian Communist Party -- Anatoly Kryuchkov,
and other committee members.
</P>
<P>
Prigarin said that in addition to "all forms of propaganda and
agitation, we shall consider the possibility of forming
detachments to defend the Mausoleum". These will not be armed
formations, he explained, "but, if it is needed, tens or even
hundreds of times more people will march to Red Square than those
that gathered at the White House in 1993."
</P>
<P>
Leader of the "Revival" Party Valery Skurlatov said that his
party members are ready to the defense of the Mausoleum when the
alarm signal is sounded."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Anpilov also promised to draw up a "black
list" of journalists, scientists, cultural leaders, and artists,
who share the idea of reburying the body of the leader, as well as
a list of "Lenin's friends."  
</P>
</TEXT>
