<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africans Urged to Invest in Former Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy Foreign
Affairs Minister Aziz Pahad today called on domestic companies to
speed up exploring investment opportunities in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
"Many international companies are pouring into that region to
seek new opportunities for investment and trade purposes," Pahad
said, noting that "if South African companies hesitate, it will
be a hesitation to their own loss."
</P>
<P>
Pahad made the remarks at a press conference briefing
reporters on a two-day visit by a government task team to the DRC
earlier this week to explore how South Africa could assist
reconstruction in the former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The group, headed by Pahad, included officials from the South
Africa Reserve Bank, the Development Bank of South Africa, and
the Departments of Finance and of Trade and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Their mission included talks with DRC President Laurent
Kabila, who took over the country in May after ousting former
president Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
"With the new attempt to form a less corrupt and more honest
government, our investors should consider that it is a good
opportunity to go in," Pahad said.
</P>
<P>
Several South African companies, especially in the mining
industry, were already involved in the DRC. "It would be good if
people go and see how to increase their involvement. I want to
believe the potential is tremendous," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Pahad, priorities in DRC include mass rural
electrification projects and industrialization, with the emphasis
on the manufacturing and mining sectors.
</P>
<P>
Pahad said the task team would submit proposals to the
government and other bodies on how South Africa could get
involved in the DRC's reconstruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
