<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Damascus Declaration FMs Ends Meeting in Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LATAKIA, SYRIA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Damascus Declaration Signatories (DDS), today issued a joint
statement emphasizing their commitment to acting in accordance
with the principles included in Arab conventions and resolutions.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement issued at the conclusion of the
meeting here this morning, Syria and Egypt submitted two working
papers on setting up a free trade zone to include the DDS members
of Egypt, Syria and six Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states to
serve as a nucleus to an Arab economic community.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups the United Arab Emirates, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,
Oman, Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
The participating ministers agreed that experts from both Syria
and Egypt would hold two meetings with their counterparts from the
(GCC) General Secretariat, one in the Saudi capital of Riyadh not
later than next September, and the other in Cairo of Egypt to
prepare a basic framework for an Arab common market.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the participants reaffirmed that a
fair and overall peace requires the restoration of Arab rights in
accordance with relevant U.N. resolutions, especially the Security
Council resolutions 242, 338 and 425.
</P>
<P>
These resolutions stipulate that Israel should withdraw
completely from the Golan Heights, south Lebanon and the occupied
Palestinian territories, and that the Palestinian people should
exercise their legitimate rights including their right for
self-determination and setting up an independent state with
Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers expressed their rejection of the attempts
made by the Israeli government to evade its commitment to a total
pullout from the Golan Heights, considering this evasion a threat
to the peace process and the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
The DDS foreign ministers called on the co-sponsors of the
Mideast peace march, particularly the U.S. to ensure complete
adherence to the commitments and pledges made by the parties
concerned to the peace talks, in view of the fact that it is the
only way to revive the peace process and bring it back to its
right course.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement said that the ministers voiced their full
support for Syria's stance and its demand for the return of its
territory occupied by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The participants expressed regret at U.S. Congress hostile
attitudes toward the Arabs, strongly condemning the recent
U.S. House of Representatives resolution on Jerusalem,
</P>
<P>
The DDS foreign ministers appealed to the U.S. Congress to
reconsider the decision on the status of the controversial holy
city.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed their great concern over the
Turkish-Israeli military and security cooperation, saying
that it poses a threat to the security of Arab states and
to the stability in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
They called it totally contrary to the charter of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference and the traditional ties
linking Turkey with Arab states.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers asked Turkey to reconsider its
cooperation with Israel and to return to its ties of cooperation
and good neighborliness with Arab states.
</P>
<P>
The statement denounced Turkey's recent incursion in northern
Iraq, underlining their respect for the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It emphasized the sovereignty of the United Arab Emirates over
the three Gulf islands of Abu Moussa and Greater and Lesser Tunbs
in its dispute with Iran, calling on both sides to enter into
serious negotiations for a peaceful solution to this issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
