<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves $800 Mln to Back Russia's Social </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) --The World Bank today announced
the approval of a 800 million U.S. dollar loan to assist Russia's
social reform program.
</P>
<P>
The program is targeted to create an effective and sustainable
system of social protection that meets the requirements of a
market economy. The program is also designed to mitigate the
adverse effects of transition on the poorest and most vulnerable
population of the society.
</P>
<P>
Russia's major economic transition of the past years has had
severe social costs, a news release from the World Bank said. As a
result of falling output and high inflation, real wages in 1996
averaged less than half of their level in 1991. Emerging open
unemployment, along with the prevailing hidden unemployment, is
estimated to have reached 15 percent by 1997. Wage and pension
arrears have accumulated rapidly.
</P>
<P>
As various surveys indicate, 25-35 percent of Russia's
population, primarily families with children, the unemployed, and
the elderly living on minimum pension, is living in poverty today,
the World Bank said. The Social Program of Reforms, approved in
February 1997, outlines the government's strategic objectives for
the period up to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's loan is repayable in 17 years, including a
5-year grace period. So far, the Bank's commitments to Russia
total about 8.3 billion dollars for 37 projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
