<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Trade Gap Up 43 Percent as Imports Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Britain's trade gap soared by 43
percent to almost 1 billion pounds (1.6 billion US dollars) during
April as import volumes rose by the highest monthly rate for 16
years.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics (ONS) estimates that the
worldwide bill for imports rose by an "underlying" 11 percent in
April, after excluding the effects of trade in oil and erratic
items such as ships, aircraft and precious stones.
</P>
<P>
Exports failed to keep pace but nevertheless also rose by a
surprise 8.3 percent. The combination of the two factors led
economists to predict another interest rate rise.
</P>
<P>
David Kern, chief economist at NatWest, gave warning that the
current overheating would force an early rate rise to 7 percent.
He also predicted measures to raise up to 3 billion pounds (4.8
billion US dollars) in next week's Budget.
</P>
<P>
The rise in imports is the result of strong domestic demand
and the appreciation of sterling to a five-year high.
</P>
<P>
Imports from Europe rose particularly rapidly, suggesting that
those countries whose currencies have depreciated most against the
pound are beginning to take advantage of their increased
competitiveness to step up sales.
</P>
<P>
Economists reacted with concern because the trade figures
corroborate other recent evidence that consumer spending may be
getting out of control.
</P>
<P>
Richard Jeggrey, group economist at Charterhouse, said: "The
trade figures are the obvious reflection of excess demand in the
UK economy."
</P>
<P>
"The economy is not capable of satisfying the level of consumer
and capital spending that is currently being recorded," he added.
</P>
<P>
Simon Briscoe, UK economist at Nikko Europe, said: "If imports
continued to grow and exports are hit in the second half of this
year, as expected, by the stronger pound, the deficit could widen
to an extent that worries the market."
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed that so far the impact of the
strength of the pound on the trade gap has been muted by falling
import prices. This effect is likely to wear off as the year
progresses.
</P>
<P>
In addition, most economists still reckon the growth in export
volumes will slow down, following the slowdown in orders reported
by recent business surveys.
</P>
<P>
They expect that when that happens, the buoyancy of imports as
a result of booming consumer spending could lead to a very rapid
deterioration in Britain's trade position.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
