<HEADLINE> Trade Surplus Registered in May in S.Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's trade account
continued to perform admirably in May, with higher exports
resulting in a record massive surplus on a month base, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to customs and excise figures released here, the
month-on-month trade surplus rose to 1.745 billion Rand (about
388 million US Dollars) in May from April's 161 million US
Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The figures also showed that the value of South African
exports improved by nine percent last month to 12.316 billion
Rand (about 2.74 billion US Dollars), compared to stagnant
imports of 10.57 billion Rand (about 2.35 billion US Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The higher-than-expected surplus lifted the trade account's
cumulative overrun to more than one billion US Dollars, almost
tripling the surplus of 373 million US Dollars in the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
The export of precious and semi-precious stones, mineral
product and agricultural produce all contributed to the increase
of the trade surplus last month, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the value of machinery and electrical equipment
imports has increased 8.6 percent so far this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
