<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Leaves for EU Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides left here today for Amsterdam, the Netherlands, to attend
a briefing Friday of the candidate countries for European Union
(EU) accession on the results of the EU Intergovernmental
Conference (IGC).
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before his departure, Clerides said that
after the Cypriot government is informed of the results of the
IGC, it will submit its views on the issue of the Cyprus'
accession to the EU.
</P>
<P>
Other countries that will attend the briefing are Poland,
Hungary, Slovakia, the Czech Republic, Romania, Bulgaria,
Slovenia, Lithuania, Estonia, Latvia and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The EU has said that Cyprus and Malta will be involved in the
next phase of the union's enlargement, while its Council of
Ministers decided, on March 6, 1995, accession negotiations will
begin with the government of Cyprus six months after the end of
the Intergovernmental Conference.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for full EU membership in July 1990.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on statements made Wednesday by British
special envoy for Cyprus, Sir David Hannay, Clerides quoted
Hannay as saying Turkey has promised help toward a Cyprus'
solution.
</P>
<P>
Hannay reportedly said that during an earlier visit to Turkey,
he was given very clear indications that the Turkish government
intended to engage constructively for a negotiated solution.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkey has not shown such indications so far on the
specific aspects of the problem, on which it intends to alter its
intransigent position, Clerides added.
</P>
<P>
Clerides will attend the U.N.-sponsored direct negotiations
with the Turkish Cypriot side, due to be held near New York
between July 9 and 13.
</P>
<P>
The talks are aimed at hammering out a comprehensive
settlement to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after the Turkish troops occupied its
northern third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
