<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests New Turkish Air Violations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has made representations
to the United Nations over fresh violations of its airspace by
Turkish military planes.
</P>
<P>
In a letter addressed to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
Nicos Agathocleous, Cyprus' permanent representative to the world
body, protested against the violation of the country's airspace
by two C-160 Turkish military planes on two separate occasions
on June 22, Cyprus News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Such unauthorised intrusions into the Nicosia Flight
Information Region and the airspace of the republic are in
violation of international air traffic rules and seriously
endanger civil aviation flights over Cyprus," Agathocleous noted.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that such violations are "in complete
disregard of the international law, the U.N. Charter and the
relevant decisions of the organization on the question of
Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot diplomat stressed that these violations, which
have heightened tension in Cyprus, occurred at a most sensitive
phase of the efforts to resume the intercommunal talks for a
solution to the Cyprus problem, due to begin near New York on
July 9.
</P>
<P>
Both Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash have confirmed their participation in the
U.N.-sponsored direct talks aimed at hammering out a
comprehensive solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops invaded and took control
of the northern third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
