<HEADLINE> Bank of Canada Raises Rates 25 Basis Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Canada's central bank today raised
its key bank rate 25 basis points to prop up the Canadian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Canada raised the bank rate by 25 basis points to
3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The operating bank for the overnight interest rate has
consequently been raised by the same amount to 3 - 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"This increase in the Bank Rate is designed to counter
excessive easing in monetary conditions and to provide support for
the currency," the bank said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
In its May Monetary Policy Report, the bank indicated that
monetary conditions were highly stimulative and that any possible
need for further easing had largely disappeared.
</P>
<P>
"Since May, persistent weakness in the Canadian dollar against
the U.S. dollar and other major currencies has in fact resulted in
further ease," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Today's rate hike by the bank is the first since 1995, and was
likely the first of many this year, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the bank cut the bank rate 11 times to its lowest
level since December 1961 to spur the sluggish Canadian economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
