<HEADLINE> France Registers Big Industrial Trade Deficit with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- France registered a 27 billion franc
(4.6 billion U.S. dollar) industrial trade deficit with the United
States in 1996, said the French State Secretariat of Industry in a
study published today.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. market remains the biggest receiver of French
investments, which amounted to 38.2 billion francs (6.6 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
France has also fallen from the ninth to the 11th largest
exporter to the U.S., mainly because of fierce competition in the
market of high-technological products.
</P>
<P>
Computer products, medical equipments, precious metal raw
materials, electronic components, and plane motors make up the
major U.S. exports to France, while France mainly sells planes,
car equipments and pharmaceutical products to the United States.
</P>
<P>
France also has taken advantage of the economic growth in the
United States to sell its food products and luxury goods, but it
met with strong competition from Italy, Britain and America's home
producers themselves in the field.
</P>
<P>
Most of the French exporters to the U.S. are affiliate
companies of French enterprises in the U.S. or Italian companies
established in France.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,200 French companies are running affiliates in the
United States, employing 400,000 workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
