<HEADLINE> Canada Calls for Binding Dispute Settlement with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Canada proposed today that the
Pacific salmon dispute with the United States be resolved through
binding dispute settlement, following the U.S. rejection of its
final offer.
</P>
<P>
Canada made a final comprehensive proposal Monday after an
intense series of talks, which ended on June 20 without agreement.
</P>
<P>
Months of talks have failed to resolve the long-standing
dispute, leaving each side to set up its own fishing arrangements.
</P>
<P>
"This outcome is very disappointing," Canadian Foreign Affairs
Minister Lloyd Axworthy said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"After months of negotiations, the U.S. offer has not changed
significantly," Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
"We need a new approach," he said. "Under the current
circumstances, the best way to resolve the issue is to refer it to
binding dispute settlement to obtain a long-term solution."
</P>
<P>
Canadian Fisheries and Oceans Minister David Anderson insisted
that his country made "a fair and constructive proposal" and the
U.S. showed "inflexibility by refusing to moderate its demands."
</P>
<P>
"However, Canada will not allow the salmon resources to suffer
the consequences. We will establish our own fishing arrangements
so that conservation is paramount," Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also called upon the United States to show
restraint in this year's fisheries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
