<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manufacturers' Prices Little Changed in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Canadian manufacturers' prices
continued to show little overall change in May, Statistics Canada
said today.
</P>
<P>
On a monthly basis, Canada's industrial product prices remained
unchanged in May from April. And the 12-month change in
manufacturing prices dropped back to 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
"This indicates that there continues to be relatively little
upward pressure on goods prices in the Canadian economy," the
federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
The industrial product price index stood at 130.7 in May, the
same level as in April.
</P>
<P>
Yet, if the effects of Canada-U.S. dollar exchange rate
movements are removed, Canada would have seen a 0.3 percent
increase in manufacturing prices in May and a 12-month price
change of 0.6 percent, the agency noted.
</P>
<P>
The May decline in the value of the U.S. dollars against the
Canadian dollar reduced the value in Canadian dollars of all
export prices quoted in U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
This reduced the month-to-month change in industrial prices
from 0.3 percent to 0.0 percent. And the impact was most
noticeable for motor vehicles, pulp, paper and wood products, the
agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
