<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-26 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Per Capita Income Triples in Past Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The per capital income in Cyprus
tripled during the past decade thanks to the thriving tourism and
a booming specially-tailored service industry for foreign business
in the island, according to a World Trade Organization (WTO)
report.
</P>
<P>
The per capita income has increased from 4,570 U.S. dollars in
1985 to approximately 13,650 dollars in 1996, said the report
tabled at a WTO meeting held in Geneva Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoted by Cyprus News Agency today, also refers to
Cyprus' application for EU membership and its efforts to harmonize
its laws, policies and institutional structure with the European
Union (EU) standards, noting that it already meets the Maastricht
convergence criteria.
</P>
<P>
Measures by Cyprus to harmonize laws and policies with the EU
and the WTO include abolition of discretionary import licensing,
revision of anti-dumping and countervailing legislation, and
introduction this year of a new foreign direct investment policy,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The EU, the report said, remains Cyprus' most important trading
partner.
</P>
<P>
The report also suggested that Cyprus could take further steps
to conform with multilateral rules such as lowering tariffs on
certain farm products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
