<HEADLINE> French Government Has No More Money to Spend: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The French Finance Minister
Dominique Strauss-Kahn said today that the government does not
have "margins of budgetary maneuver" to spend more money on
social and economic projects.
</P>
<P>
"All makes think that there is a slippage at the level of
budget and social account," said Strauss-Kahn at a forum on
economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
During his legislative campaign, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin,
then the leader of the opposition Socialist Party, promised to use
public budget to create 350,000 jobs for the youths.
</P>
<P>
But Jospin failed to put the project into the primary agenda in
his declaration of general policy before the parliament last week.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the French Senate today, Jospin admitted that he
was faced with "contradictory demands" from both his electoral
supporters and France's European partners.
</P>
<P>
"We will effectively keep to the contradictory demands of a
growth to support, an unemployment to make drop, and at the same
time a control of public accounts," said Jospin.
</P>
<P>
Strauss-Kahn said that the budget reduction planned by the
budget law drafted by the former government of Prime Minister
Alain Juppe has not been made in the primary months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The budget such as it was voted has not been mastered during
the primary months of 1997," he said.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that the government of Prime Minister Jospin will
see to it that the 1997 and 1998 public deficits of France will be
"coherent" with the need to launch the European single currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
