<HEADLINE> Turkey Denounces Alien Support for PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish military today accused
some neighboring countries of supporting the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) rebels.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with reporters in the southeastern city of
Diyarbakir, Colonel Husnu Dag, spokesman for Chief of the General
Staff Ismail Hakki Karadayi claimed that Iran, Greece, Serbia,
Cyprus, Armenia and Syria have given the rebels political,
financial and training support.
</P>
<P>
Turkey made such allegations before but they were denied.
</P>
<P>
"This support has been confirmed by documents obtained by the
Turkish military and confessions of those terrorists captured
alive," reports reaching here quoted Dag as saying.
</P>
<P>
A number of arrested PKK members, among whom nine were Syrians,
were reportedly shown to reporters at the news briefing.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that these countries should realize that
they themselves might be victims of the extremist activities
someday.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Oguz Kaleli, also official of the General Staff, told
the news conference that it was confirmed that Greece and Syria
have joined hands in backing the PKK.
</P>
<P>
Citing confessions of some PKK captives, Kaleli said that
some PKK rebels had been given shelter in the Greek capital of
Athens, and they had received political training in Syria.
</P>
<P>
He added that retired Greek officers trained PKK rebels on how
to operate missiles.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today said that 157 Greek
parliamentarians have signed a joint petition to invite PKK leader
Abdullah Ocalan to visit Athens.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly criticized the countries for their
backing of the PKK that has fought a 13-year-old separatist war
in eastern and southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Some 50,000-strong Turkish government troops have performed
massive military operations since mid-May in an attempt to wipe
out the PKK rebels stationed in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's cross-border campaign has drawn sharp criticism from
the Arab world and some Western countries as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
