<HEADLINE> Industry Group Urges Swift Structural Reforms in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Federation of German Industry
(BDI) today called for urgent structural reforms in Germany in a
bid to stem a decline in the country's competitiveness on the
world market.
</P>
<P>
Although Germany exports had experienced a continuing upswing
since the beginning of this year, the nation's share in the
fast-growing world market dropped in 1996 and is expected to
continue to lose ground in the current year, said a latest
economic report issued today by the BDI, Germany's premier
business lobby.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Germany saw a foreign direct investment inflow
plummet from 18.2 billion marks (10.6 billion U.S. dollars) in
1995 to only 1.1 billion marks (640 million dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Both are indications of the declining competitiveness of
Germany as an industrial base and of the urgent need of structural
reforms," the BDI said.
</P>
<P>
The group called on political parties to come up with swift and
consistent reforms in the country's taxation and pension systems
in a bid to relieve enterprises of the heavy burden of high labor
costs.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that the reforms should be targeted to spur
economic growth and bolster investment and should not fall a
victim to political calculations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
