<HEADLINE> Turkish PM-Designate to Submit Cabinet List Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister-designate
Mesut Yilmaz is to submit his cabinet list to President Suleyman
Demirel early next week.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters following a meeting with Demirel,
Yilmaz said that the president had promised to appove a
government supported by four parties in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, chairman of the second largest Motherland Party
(ANAP), said that the cabinet list might be delivered to the
presidential palace Monday or Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister-designate today started the second round
of talks with Democratic Left Party (DSP) leader Bulent
Ecevit and Republican People's Party (CHP) leader Deniz
Baykal in an effort to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
The DSP and CHP leaders had earlier expressed their full
support for the proposed government, but Baykal said that his
party had no plan to take part in the government.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with Ecevit earlier today, Yilmaz told
reporters that he and the DSP leader agreed that a joint
commission should start working Friday on the structure and
program of the new government.
</P>
<P>
He said that Ecevit will be the deputy prime minister of the
proposed government, adding that he also hoped to see the
participation of Democratic Turkey Party (DTP) leader Husamettin
Cindoruk in the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Cindoruk, whose party enjoys seven seats in the parliament,
had said that all DTP deputies would be supporters of the new
government, describing backing the proposed government as "a
national duty."
</P>
<P>
On June 20, President Demirel asked Yilmaz to form a new
government to replace the resigned Welfare Party (RP)-True Path
Party (DYP) coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Islamic Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan, under pressure from
both the military and the DYP over his government's failure to
curb the rapidly expanding fundamentalism in the secular
republic, resigned on June 18.
</P>
<P>
DYP leader Tansu Ciller, who had planned to take over
premiership from Erbakan, was annoyed by Demirel's appointment of
Yilmaz to form a new government, calling it "a Cankaya
(presidential palace) coup."
</P>
<P>
She said that the RP-DYP alliance with the nationalist Grand
Unity Party could defeat Yilmaz's efforts to set up a new
government in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, however, expressed optimism about the new government
he is trying to form, saying that he believed the new government
would win a vote of confidence in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the developments in the coming days will
expand the margin. The outcome of the vote will not be very
close," the ANAP leader said.
</P>
<P>
DYP parliamentarian Isilay Saygin resigned earlier today and
jointed the ANAP, increasing the number of ANAP deputies to 130
in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
For the time being, the ANAP, DSP, CHP and DTP enjoy a total
of 254 seats in the 550-seat parliament, not enough to obtain a
parliamentary majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
