<HEADLINE> Tennessee Teenager Ordered to Stand Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A judge in Tennessee of the
United States has set a November 10 trial date for the youth
accused of shooting two teachers and a student in 1995, killing
two of them.
</P>
<P>
Three mental health experts have testified, with differing
prognoses of the defendant, Jamie Rouse, The United Press
International reported.
</P>
<P>
One psychologist said Rouse was sane, one called him insane,
and the third testified the teenager would be ready to stand trial
in six to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
The judge said Rouse's trial should begin in November, two
years after he allegedly gunned down three people in Richland High
School in Lynnville, Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
Only teacher Carol Yancy survived to talk about the attack.
</P>
<P>
Yancy was in the Lawrence County, Tennessee, courtroom for the
hearing and told the court she's disappointed by the length of
time it has taken to bring Rouse to trial.
</P>
<P>
Tennessee law prohibits the death penalty for teenagers but
Rouse could be sentenced to life in prison, if convicted.
</P>
<P>
A second teen, Stephen Abbott, who drove Rouse to the high
school and helped plan the shooting rampage, already has been
convicted for his part in the slayings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
