<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Mortgages Rate Drops to Lowest in 4 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Average interest rates on
30-year, fixed-rate mortgages in the U.S. declined this week to
the lowest level in four months.
</P>
<P>
The average decreased to 7.58 percent from 7.61 percent a week
earlier, the U.S. Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. said today.
</P>
<P>
It was the lowest rate since the week ended on February 20,
five weeks before the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) tightened
monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
After the Fed tightened the monetary policy with increasing
the U.S. federal fund rate by a quarter percentage point on March
25, the average rates of 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages rose to a
seven-month high of 8.18 percent for the week ended April 3 and
has declined in nine of the 12 weeks since.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 15-year mortgages, a popular option for those
refinancing mortgages in the U.S., averaged 7.13 percent this
week, also the lowest since the week ended February 20 and down
from 7.14 percent a week earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
