<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Chamber of Commerce Hails NAFTA Huge Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The first three years of the
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), which was formally
set up on January 1, 1994, have been a huge success for American
business and workers, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce said today.
</P>
<P>
"Under NAFTA, American companies have increased their exports
to Mexico by 35.7 percent. In 1996 alone, exports to Mexico were
up to 23 percent while imports from Mexico grew just 18 percent,"
noted Willard W. Workman, chamber vice president for international
affairs. For instance, he said, U.S. automobile exports to Mexico
grew from 1.4 percent of the total Mexican market before NAFTA to
24.6 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 57 billion U.S. dollars in export to Mexico support more
than 1 million U.S. jobs, not counting the jobs created by imports
from Mexico, Workman added.
</P>
<P>
He also said the stable trade and investment rules under NAFTA
have given U.S. companies a clear advantage over their Asian and
European competitors trying to export to the growing Mexican
market. American businesses increased their market share in Mexico
from 70 percent in 1994 to 75 percent in 1995, and it continues to
grow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
