<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Strikes Down Key Gun Control Act Provision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Supreme Court, in a
5-4 decision Friday, struck down a key portion of the Brady Act,
which requires local sheriffs and police chiefs to conduct
background searches on handgun purchasers.
</P>
<P>
The narrow majority says the federal government cannot force
the states to administer a program to enforce federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
The decision does not affect the federal government's ability
to regulate firearms, but does affect the dwindling number of
states without instant computer background checks.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the law, the federal government must make a
federal database available to the states by November 30 next year.
</P>
<P>
Writing for the majority, Justice Antonin Scalia says, "We held
in New York (vs. United States) that Congress cannot compel the
states to enact or enforce a federal regulatory program. Today we
hold that Congress cannot circumvent that prohibition by
conscripting the state's officers directly."
</P>
<P>
He adds, "The federal government may neither issue directives
requiring the states to address particular problems, nor command
the states's officers, or those of their political subdivisions,
to administer or enforce a federal regulatory program."
</P>
<P>
Justice John Paul Stevens, who led the dissent, says, "When
Congress exercises the powers delegated to it by the Constitution,
it may impose affirmative obligations on...state and local
governments as well as ordinary citizens."
</P>
<P>
Today's decision reverses lower-court rulings in favor of the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
