<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Invests in Hydro-power Project in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government signed an
agreement here today with Australia's Snow Mountain Engineering
Corporation (SMEC) on implementation of the West Seti hydro
electricity project.
</P>
<P>
According to the Water Resources Ministry, the 750,000
kw-capacity West Seti hydro electricity project, in far western
Nepal, is to be developed into an export-oriented power project.
</P>
<P>
This is the first large hydro electricity project in Nepal ever
involving a foreign private company.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government and the SMEC West Seti Hydro-electric
Corporation Ltd. already signed an agreement in May on export of
electricity generated under the project.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stipulates that the SMEC has the right to control
and regulate the whole water basin of the Seti River and to sell
power to India.
</P>
<P>
An average of 3.1 billion units electricity will be generated
under the project, said the Water Resources Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the project will begin in 1999 and is
expected to be completed by the end of 2004 at a cost of about one
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has a huge hydroelectric potential of 83 million kw, but
less than one percent has been utilized so far.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's water resources development policy,
domestic and foreign private sector is encouraged to invest in
this sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
