<HEADLINE> Sino-Portuguese JLG Should Focus on Main Task: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison
Group (JLG) should make great efforts to quicken the handling of
main transitional affairs in Macao, a top Chinese official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Guo Jiading, chief representative of the Chinese side of the
JLG, said at the Macao International Airport after returning from
Lisbon on conclusion of the 29th plenary session of JLG that the
joint group should focus its efforts on the issues concerning with
stable transition and smooth handover of power in Macao.
</P>
<P>
"Now that we have settled such issues as the Orient Foundation,
the revision of the contract on gambling monopoly and the
establishment of a new foundation, we should move our focus to the
main tasks," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The localization of civil service, the use of Chinese as an
official language and the localization of law, which are called
the "three leading issues", and handling of the transfer of
archives and government assets are among the main tasks, he said.
</P>
<P>
A working panel on the transfer of archives and government
assets should be established immediately since the two sides
reached agreement on the setup of the panel four years ago, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Lisbon-based Orient Foundation, which is accused by local
media of siphoning money from Macao to Portugal, will have to
spend most of its income in Macao, and must report its expenditure
to the Macao government, according to a consensus reached in the
29th session.
</P>
<P>
The Macao Tourism and Amusement Company (STDM), which
previously supplied money to the Orient Foundation, stopped doing
so from January 1, 1996. It will have to divert the money to a new
foundation called the "Macao Development and Cooperation
Foundation."
</P>
<P>
The new foundation will be set up soon by the present Macao
government and will belong to the Macao Special Administrative
Regional Government by December 20, 1999. It is aimed at promoting
arts, academic activities, science and technology, education,
social affairs and welfare in Macao, according to the consensus.
</P>
</TEXT>
