<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk-Chief Executive's Office Expresses Concern over Hasty Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the Office of
the Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) today expressed grave concern over the hasty passage of
legislation in the past few days, including several labor laws.
</P>
<P>
In response to press inquires, the spokesman said the HKSAR
would review the newly passed bills because drastic changes might
adversely affect the community and would not be in the interest of
long-term labor relations.
</P>
<P>
The bills had been pushed through very quickly without careful
consideration, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the labor legislation had not been fully
considered by the Labor Advisory Board, a well-established
mechanism for discussion of labor issues.
</P>
<P>
"The SAR government will assess the social and economic
implications which these changes have on society and take all
necessary action," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the Crimes (Amendment)(No.2) Bill 1996 passed on June 24,
the spokesman said Article 23 of the Basic Law clearly states that
the HKSAR shall enact laws on its own to prohibit any act of
treason, secession, sedition and subversion.
</P>
<P>
"We have already indicated that these laws which might have
wide implications are best left to the first SAR legislature and
that legislative proposals should be worked out after wide public
consultation," he said.
</P>
<P>
An editorial of a local newspaper also points out today that
the hasty passing of dozens of laws at the last meeting of the
Legislative Council is not an ideal choice from any point of view.
"Why not leave them for more careful deliberations later?" it
says.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the "political reform" package imposed
unilaterally by the British side, which sabotaged the "through
train" arrangement, the last Legislative Council under the Hong
Kong-British government will be dissolved on June 30, 1997,
according to a decision of the Ninth Session of China's Eighth
National People's Congress in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
