<HEADLINE> Schumacher Wins Practice for French Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- World championship leader Michael
Schumacher of Germany, driving a Ferrari, sets the fastest time in
opening practice in rain for Sunday's French Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old double world champion clocked a best time of
one minute 18.339 seconds in Magny-Cours, 1.4 seconds better than
his nearest rival Italian Giancarlo Fisichella's best effort in
his Jordan as the track dried out in the closing minutes.
</P>
<P>
His Ferrari team mate Eddie Irvine of Britain, whose future is
under threat from the Italian team's admiration for Finn Mika Salo
of Tyrrell, was not given a chance to go out on slicks and wound
up down in 20th place out of the 22 runners.
</P>
<P>
Irvine's contract expires at the end of the year and Ferrari's
option to renew it expires at the end of July. Their inactivity
-- despite Schumacher's forthright support for Irvine -- has
suggested they are considering approaching Salo to succeed the
Northern Ireland man next season.
</P>
<P>
Italian Jarno Trulli, replacing the injured Olivier Panis in
the Prost team, was 19th fastest.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Panis suffered double fractures to both legs when he
crashed during the Canadian Grand Prix two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Tarso Marques, the 21-year-old Brazilian who was called up to
replace Trulli at Minardi was 14th fastest while Norberto Fontana
of Argentina who replaced broken arm victim Italian Gianni
Morbidelli at Sauber, wound up 18th on his debut. 
</P>
</TEXT>
