<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> I'm Full of Confidence in the Future: Tycoon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong tycoon Li Ka-shing
expressed confidence in the future of Hong Kong in an interview
today.
"The return of Hong Kong to its motherland is a historic moment
the Chinese people have long been expecting. I'm very proud to be
a Chinese," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of property developer Cheung Kong (Holdings) Ltd. and
conglomerate Hutchison Whampoa Ltd., Li was named by the Forbes
magazine one of the world's 10 richest individuals in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"When I was a kid, I saw the miseries and sufferings of our
country and people inflicted by foreign invasions," he recalled.
"As a Chinese living in Hong Kong for so many years, it is hard
to express by words my feelings to see my motherland growing
stronger day by day."
</P>
<P>
He said it would have been impossible for China to recover Hong
Kong by peaceful means if the country had been as weak as it was
more than 150 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Having been involved in return of Hong Kong-related affairs
ever since the Sino-British Joint Declaration was signed in 1984,
Li has witnessed developments in Hong Kong throughout its
transitional period.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong is now going through a "very good"
period both economically and in terms of people's morale and that
Hong Kong people's confidence in the future keeps growing.
</P>
<P>
Two fundamental factors have contributed to Hong Kong's smooth
transition, he said. "One is the principle of 'one country, two
systems', a policy that works for the overall national interests
of the country; and the other is rapid economic development in
China's interior areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the "one country, two systems" policy has
dispelled worries of many Hong Kong citizens by ensuring that Hong
Kong's existing economic system and way of life will remain
unchanged.
The policies of reform and opening to the outside world and rapid
economic development have made China more powerful and benefited
the Hong Kong economy, too, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is a great pity that Mr. Deng Xiaoping is unable to see
what happens today," Li, who met Deng on many occasions, sighed
with regret.
</P>
<P>
Deng, chief architect of China's reform and opening up and
creator of the "one country, two systems" principle, passed away
in Beijing last February. He had repeatedly expressed the wish to
visit Hong Kong when the handover occurs.
</P>
<P>
"It is comforting that, under the leadership of the central
authorities with President Jiang Zemin at the core, China is
becoming richer and more powerful, with its international status
rising day by day," Li said.
</P>
<P>
He said that every time he met with Jiang and other state
leaders, he was impressed by the Chinese government's firm
determination to carry out the Basic Law and the policy of "one
country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
"From my own experience and China's course of development, I
have reached this conclusion, that the future of Hong Kong is in
our own hands," he said. "I am full of confidence in Hong Kong's
future."
</P>
<P>
He said that after July 1, Hong Kong will become a focus of
world attention and that people all over the world will be
watching how Hong Kongers perform in the new era.
</P>
<P>
"We must show the cohesive force of our nation to the rest of
the world and work together to maintain Hong Kong's long-term
prosperity," he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
