<HEADLINE> S. Arabian FM Stresses United Arab Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia's Foreign Minister
Prince Saud Al-Faisal Al-Saud stressed here today that a united
and firm position of Arab countries and a change of Israel's
intransigent policy are the guarantee for a restart of the
deadlocked Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Faisal made the remarks at a meeting with his Lebanese
counterpart Farez Boueiz in the latter's office.
</P>
<P>
He said that he briefed Boueiz the outcome of a two-day
meeting of foreign ministers of the Damascus Declaration
signatories,which ended in Syria's Mediterranean resort of
Lattakia Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of Egypt, Syria and six Gulf Arab states,
namely Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United
Arab Emirates, agreed that either there is a just and comprehensive
peace based on international resolutions and the land-for-peace
principle, or there is no peace in the region, Faisal noted.
</P>
<P>
Faisal welcomed the idea of establishing a common Arab market,
adding that the issue of a regional economic summit scheduled to
be held in Qatar next November will be discussed by Arab foreign
ministers when they meet in Cairo in September.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria have said that they will boycott the Qatar
economic summit, the fourth of its kind, due to Israel'
participation. They called for an Arab economic summit to take
its place.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi foreign minister, who is accompanying Crown Prince
Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz in the current visit to Lebanon,
underlined the significance of the visit, the first by a senior
member of the Saudi royal family since 1975. Faisal noted that the
visit would "promote the brotherly relations between the two
countries."
</P>
<P>
He clarified that "the kingdom of Saudi Arabia has always
stood on Lebanon's side, supporting its sovereignty,
independence and integrity of its territory, and has proved
this through the efforts exerted during the painful time," a
reference to the Lebanese 1975-90 civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi crown prince, heading an entourage exceeding 140
people, arrived in Lebanon from Syria Thursday afternoon for a
three-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
