<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Symphony Rehearsed for HK's Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A symphony specially composed to
mark the return of Hong Kong to China is being rehearsed here for
celebration performance.
</P>
<P>
The symphony, titled 1997 -- Heaven, Earth, People, is composed
by Tan Dun, a famous composer born in China and now living in the
United States. It consists of three movements.
</P>
<P>
The first movement, played by cellos, musical bells -- an
ancient Chinese instrument, and a children choir, is meant to
display the traditions of the Chinese nation.
</P>
<P>
The second movement, a concerto featuring musical bells and
cellos and divided into three sub-movements titled Fire, Water,
and Metal, is intended to demonstrate the harmony of the nature.
</P>
<P>
The symphony ends in a chorus titled Harmony of Heaven, Earth
and People, implying that all the beings become one in harmony.
</P>
<P>
Part of the symphony will be performed to celebrate the
establishment of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
The whole symphony will be performed in Hong Kong and Beijing
on July 4 and July 5, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
