<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajik Government, Opposition Sign Historic Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Tajik government and the
opposition signed a landmark peace accord in Moscow today, ending
the tiny central Asian nation's four-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
The deal was signed by Tajik President Imomali Rakhmonov and
Islamic opposition leader Sayid Abdullo Nuri at a ceremony in the
Kremlin hosted by Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to exchange prisoners of war and establish
a Nuri-led 26-member National Commission for Reconciliation, with
places to be divided equally between each side.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmonov will remain president but 30 percent of government
posts must be given over to the opposition under the accord.
</P>
<P>
Opposition forces must integrate with government troops or lay
down their weapons and fresh parliamentary elections must be held
by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Praising the accord, Yeltsin said, "This day should go down as
a remarkable page in the history of Tajikistan. It brings an end
to one of the longest and bitterest conflicts on Earth."
</P>
<P>
Russia will try to help Tajikistan proceed along the road of
peace and national reconciliation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since Tajikistan gained independence in September 1991 after
the collapse of the Soviet Union, conflicts among different
political, religious and ethnic groups intensified.
</P>
<P>
Islamic opposition forces, the main rival of the Tajik
government, set up bases in mountainous border areas between
Tajikistan and Afghanistan and launched a guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale fighting ended after the Tajik government and the
opposition forces signed a truce last December, but sporadic
clashes continued until today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
