<HEADLINE> Lesotho Calm Despite Major Political Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Despite Prime Minister Ntsu
Mokehle's breakaway to form the Lesotho Congress for Democracy
this month, a senior Lesotho government official today described
the present situation in the country as " being stable " under
the ruling Basutholand Congress Party (BCP).
</P>
<P>
Lesotho's Justice, Law and Constitutional Minister Sephiri
Motanyane said that Lesotho, which was poised to hold
elections next year, was not anticipating upheavals in the wake
of Mokehle's move.
</P>
<P>
Motanyane, who is on a visit here, made the statement after
briefing Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe of events in Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
"There is no change because Mokehle still receives
overwhelming support from ministers and members of the National
Assembly," he said, adding, "regardless of his recent political
move, he will remain the country's prime minister, and there will
be no change in the way of running government."
</P>
<P>
Motanyane said, "'Mokehle formed a new party because he was
prompted by the in-fighting within the ruling party, and he saw
that as a political solution to the problem."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe is currently Chairman of
the Organization of African Unity, and of Organ on Politics,
Defense and Security of the Southern African Development
Community.
</P>
<P>
There have been fears that violence might erupt in Lesotho
after Mokehle left the BCP to form his own party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
