<HEADLINE> Australia's Wool Industry Threatened by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Australia's wool industry was in
danger unless wool growers improved the quality of their product
by reducing contamination in wool bales, Primary Industries
Minister John Anderson warned today.
</P>
<P>
Anderson said buyers in Italy, France, Germany, Britain, Japan
and China had threatened to stop buying Australian wool unless the
level of contamination was reduced.
</P>
<P>
He announced a working party, comprising leaders of the wool
industry and government backbencher David Hawker, would be set up
to consider the best ways to improve the standard of wool exports.
</P>
<P>
It would consider how the industry could eliminate the use of
polypropylene hay baling twine, a chief contaminant of wool, the
benefits of a phased move to nylon wool packs and quality
assurance schemes.
</P>
<P>
The minister said even shears and bale-handling equipment
sometimes ended up in the bales sent to overseas customers.
</P>
<P>
Customers "were adamant that we don't seem to be recognizing,
despite warnings for decades, that it is putting the industry's
future at risk," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Some of them are quite openly warning that they will look to
alternative fibers in the future if we don't do something serious
about it," he added.
</P>
<P>
The working party, set up after Anderson held talks with chief
executives of the Australian Wool Exchange, the Wool Council, the
Australian Wool Research and Promotion Organization and other
industry groups, will report its suggestions in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
