<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong: International Financial Center Built On Confidence (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Sergio Rail, a Brazilian of
Chinese descent, who oversees a Dutch bank's business in China,
has been living a flying life since he came to Hong Kong two years
ago. Two or three days a week he stays in Hong Kong but otherwise
rushes between six branches and representative offices in the
inland areas of China.
</P>
<P>
With four days left before Hong Kong returns to China, Rail
said: "I still don't know where I'll be on June 30, but surely
I'll watch TV. It's a historic event, and I'm very happy to see it
and experience it."
</P>
<P>
"Being a Hong Kong resident, I hope this is the beginning of a
great future," said the banker working for ABN Amro Bank of the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
"The transition in Hong Kong has been going on smoothly. For
people living here, business is as usual," said Rail, adding that
he might spend the day working rather than celebrating.
</P>
<P>
ABN Amro has been in Hong Kong for 91 years, according to Rail.
In the Asia-Pacific region, Hong Kong has been the top profit
maker for his bank, the world's 14th largest. After July 1, the
bank will continue to base its regional headquarters in Hong Kong
and go all out to expand its presence in the rest of China, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Rail said the bank has confidence in Hong Kong's future.
"Because we have confidence in Hong Kong people. They are
extraordinarily adaptable, quick and focused. It is Hong Kong
people who have really made this place what it is," he said.
</P>
<P>
Like Serge Rail, tens of thousands of professionals have come
to this international financial center, working for banks, funds,
insurance companies, accounting agencies and securities firms.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the world's third largest banking center, where
some 500 authorized institutions from 43 countries and regions
have established their presence, including licensed banks,
restricted license banks, deposit-taking companies and
representative offices of foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
Of the world's top 100 banks, 82 have had offices here, among
which 73 are operating with a full banking license. Around 67
percent of banking business is done in foreign currencies. Most
recently, Hong Kong has been the largest supplier of syndicated
loans and the largest debt issuer in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has the world's fourth largest gold bullion market,
fifth largest foreign exchange market, seventh largest derivatives
market, eighth largest stock market, one of the world's leading
insurance markets and the most vibrant bond market in Asia.
</P>
<P>
In addition, there are over 1,300 mutual funds in Hong Kong,
which manage assets totaling 100 billion US dollars and invest
widely in securities markets both in China's inland areas and
abroad. Hong Kong is also the second largest center of venture
capital in the Asia-pacific region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong: International Financial Center Built On Confidence (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Andrew Lo, chairman of the Hong Kong Investment Funds
Association (IFA), said that the return of Hong Kong to China will
bring tremendous opportunities for Hong Kong's funds management
industry.
</P>
<P>
"China has a huge population of 1.2 billion and a huge pool of
savings but few investment channels. There is a potentially huge
market for fund managers," said the IFA chairman.
</P>
<P>
Lo added that, as a long-term investment, funds play a
stabilizing role on an international financial market like Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Vincent Cheng, executive director of the Hong Kong and Shanghai
Banking Corporation Ltd, said: "The way things will go in the
future will depend on China's economic reform and open-up
policies, its readiness to implement the promise of 'one country,
two systems' and the competitive edge of Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Apart from some natural conditions that make Hong Kong flourish
as a global financial hub, Cheng pointed out that Hong Kong's
success relies largely on the diligence of the people here and
their faith and confidence in the future. "Investment is made on
the basis of confidence," said the Hong Kong banker.
</P>
<P>
His views are shared by Anthony Leung, a managing director of
the Chase Manhatten Bank, who overseas the American bank's
regional business here.
</P>
<P>
Also a member of the HKSAR's Executive Council, Leung said
that, to preserve Hong Kong's status as an international financial
center, there are five fundamental and indispensable elements --
the rule of law, a level playing field, free flow of information,
an efficient and corruption-free civil service, and law and order.
</P>
<P>
Leung said that, in the foreseeable future, Hong Kong will
continue to be the best place where foreign investors can seek
business opportunities in China's inland areas. Meanwhile,
enterprises from inland areas can meet their business partners in
Hong Kong, where so many multinational companies base their
regional headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 15 years, more than 60 percent of overseas
investment flowing into China's inland areas came from or through
Hong Kong. Today, 32 enterprises from the inland areas have been
listed at the Hong Kong stock exchange. They have raised a total
of 6.6 billion US dollars by issuing H shares.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a number of local China-backed companies issuing what
is called as "red chip" shares, have had a growing presence in the
local market. H shares and Red Chips now account for about ten
percent of total market capitalization in Hong Kong's stock
market.
</P>
<P>
Edgar Cheng, chairman of the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong said
that Hong Kong should attract more and better enterprises from the
inland areas to its bourse. Meanwhile, Hong Kong should preserve
its monetary system and supervisory framework in accordance with
the international standard so as to draw foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Anthony Neoh, chairman of the Securities and Futures
Commission, expressed the same view. He said: "The ultimate
objective of supervision is to keep confidence in the market."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong: International Financial Center Built On Confidence (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong is the second largest in Asia
next only to Japan's. Its current market capitalization hits 600
billion US dollars, and the Hang Seng Index, the market indicator
for blue-chips, has increased by a big margin so far this year.
The stock market not only serves Hong Kong but has also become an
important fund-raising source for Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Exchange Fund, or its foreign exchange reserves,
reached 66.6 billion US dollars in May, 1997, ranking the seventh
in the world.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Yam, chief executive of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA) estimated that, if the 20-billion-US dollar Land Fund is
added, Hong Kong's total foreign exchange reserves will exceed 86
billion US dollars when Hong Kong becomes a Special Administrative
Region of China. "This will put Hong Kong in the fourth or fifth
place in the world in terms of the size of foreign exchange
reserves," said Yam.
</P>
<P>
However, as the HKMA chief executive said, the success of today
does not guarantee success for tomorrow. In his view, the historic
change on July 1, when China resumes the exercise of sovereignty
over Hong Kong, will mark not only the beginning of a new era for
Hong Kong, but also the beginning of a new era for its financial
sector.
</P>
<P>
"We need increasingly to rely on our innovative and dynamic
spirit to maintain and strengthen Hong Kong's status as an
international financial center," said the 49-year-old Yam who has
assumed his present post since 1993.
</P>
<P>
In his view, the spirit of "One country, Two systems" gives
Hong Kong ample room to be creative and to ensure the continued
prosperity of Hong Kong. He believed that the financial
relationship between Hong Kong and inland areas will be based on
the principle of one country, two currencies, two monetary systems
and two monetary authorities, as the Chinese government has
stressed time and again.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law has laid down a clear legal foundation to ensure
that the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) formulate
its own monetary and financial policies.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong dollar, as the legal tender in the HKSAR, will
continue to circulate and be freely convertible. Free flow of
capital within, into and out of Hong Kong will be maintained and
the Exchange Fund will be managed and controlled by the HKSAR
government.
</P>
<P>
China's determination to fulfill its commitment to "One
country, two systems" is the cornerstone that supports confidence
in the future among Hong Kong's financial circles.
</P>
<P>
Dr Miron Mushkat, chief economist of Lehman Brothers, a global
investment banking giant, said: "The historic change on July 1
will not adversely affect Hong Kong's status as an international
financial center in the next five or ten years." On the contrary,
he stressed that the change will prove beneficial for the Hong
Kong economy in the short term. Thanks to greater economic
integration between Hong Kong and inland areas, Hong Kong will
play an increasingly important role as a good middleman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Chief Executive's Office Welcomes PLA Arrival Details </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive's Office of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region today (HKSAR) welcomed
the arrangements for the entry of the People's Liberation Army
(PLA) Garrison into Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the office said the first group of 509 military
personnel of the PLA Garrison being the advance elements would
arrive in Hong Kong from Shenzhen via Huanggang Port in 39
vehicles at 9 pm on June 30.
</P>
<P>
They would be stationed at the Prince of Wales Barracks,
Stanley Fort, Stonecutters Island and Shek Kong Camp, and would
take up their duties at midnight, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The second group of about 4,000 personnel, who form the main
contingent of the PLA Garrison in Hong Kong, will arrive in Hong
Kong at 6 am on July 1 simultaneously by land, sea and air routes
in 10 ships, six helicopters, 21 armored vehicles and 400 other
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The land forces will enter through Sha Tau Kok Port, Man Kam To
Port and Huanggang Port.
</P>
<P>
The ten naval vessels will sail from Shenzhen to Stonecutters
Island and the helicopters will fly over Man Kam To control point
to Shek Kong air base.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR Government will make suitable arrangements to
facilitate the arrival of the PLA Garrison to carry out its duties
in Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
