<HEADLINE> Philippine Defense Minister Joins Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Minister Renato
de Villa today formally entered the ranks of the ruling Lakas-NUCD
party, setting the stage for a struggle for the endorsement of
President Fidel Ramos in the 1998 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The Ramos-chaired ruling party earlier set June 30 as the
deadline for those presidential aspirants seeking Ramos'
anointment as the party's presidential candidate to join the
party.
</P>
<P>
Attending de Villa's low-profile oath-taking ceremony were
Ramos and Speaker of the House of Representatives Jose de Venecia,
a main rival for de Villa in contending for Ramos' support. De
Venecia is general-secretary of the governing party.
</P>
<P>
Other contenders for Ramos' backing include his economic
adviser Emilio Osmena, Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo and his
younger sister, Senator Leticia Ramos-Shahani.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo, who is not a Lakas member, has said he will join the
party at a proper time.
</P>
<P>
Political observers said a fierce struggle for Ramos' backing
would possibly lead to the party's breakup.
</P>
<P>
In the presidential election in 1992, Ramos broke away from the
Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino party and formed the Lakas after
losing nomination in the party's national convention. But he won
the polls with the strong support of former president Corazon
Aquino. 
</P>
