<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laws To Be Enforced In Hong Kong (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislative body has
decided that 10 national laws will be enforced in Hong Kong after
July 1.
</P>
<P>
The 26th meeting of the Standing Committee of the Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC) discussed a proposal on a draft
decision to add or delete national laws to or from Annex 3 of
the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
According to the draft, the five laws to be added to Annex 3 of
the Basic Law are: the National Flag Law of the People's Republic
of China (PRC), Regulations on Consular Privileges and Immunity in
the PRC, the Law on the National Emblem of the PRC, the Law on
China's Territorial Waters and Adjoining Areas, and the Garrison
Law of the PLA Troops Stationed in the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The law to be deleted from Annex 3 of the Basic Law is the
Order on the National Emblem of the PRC Proclaimed by the Central
People's Government Attached: Design of the national emblem,
Notes, and Instructions on Use.
</P>
<P>
Cao Zhi, secretary-general of the NPC Standing Committee,
explained the draft decision. Six national laws were part of the
Basic Law of 1990, Cao said. The NPC and the Standing Committee
have made laws related to national defence and foreign affairs
which were outside the HKSAR's rule according to the Basic Law,
and some needed to be added to the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Cao said that the draft decision was to delete the Order on the
National Emblem of the PRC Proclaimed by the Central People's
Government Attached from Annex 3 of the Basic Law. The reason is
that Law on the National Emblem of the PRC covers the Order.
</P>
<P>
The draft decision does not delete a resolution on the national
capital, and the national anthem and national flag of the PRC made
by the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference on
September 27, 1949.
</P>
<P>
Cao explained that the resolution made stipulations on the
national capital and national anthem and national flag.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
