<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Shares in market bellwether BHP
dragged the Australian sharemarket into positive territory today,
outweighing the influences of options expiries and portfolio
reshuffling.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished 2.5 points up at
2702.4, after trading in a 14.1 point range.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP today announced its annual profit for the
year to May 31 was 307.5 million US dollars, a 60 percent slide
from the previous year's result of 784.5 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The result was dragged down by a net abnormal loss of nearly
750 million US dollars because of a massive writedown of some
assets.
</P>
<P>
Shaw Stockbroking's Mark Murray said the result was in line
with expectations and the market has written off the abnormals as
a "one-off."
</P>
<P>
"The stock was sold off early after the results were announced
and then rallied," Murray said.
</P>
<P>
BHP's shares closed nine cents firmer at 19.15 Australian
dollars, on volume of 28.84 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was one point higher at 4261.1 while
the all resources index rose four to 1499.0.
</P>
<P>
Among other resources stocks, shares in diversified miner Rio
Tinto fell 27.2 cents to 22.57 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was 15.7 points down at 1472.5. In Sydney, gold
bullion closed at 337.45 US dollars per fine ounce, down from
yesterday's close of 338.10 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 639.87 million shares valued at 2136.52
Australian dollars (1.602 billion US dollars), with rises
outnumbering falls 638 to 520. 
</P>
</TEXT>
