<HEADLINE> Hong Kongers After Handover Souvenirs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- As the day of Hong Kong's return
to China is impending, a craze for return souvenirs hit residents
in this metropolis with many of them queuing up for stamps,
magnetic cards, watches and other keepsakes, which are for
commemorative purpose.
</P>
<P>
Long lines appeared this morning outside the ten selling
outlets across the city for a set of commemorative coins issued by
the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
</P>
<P>
The set, composed of seven coins at a total value of 18.8
dollars, were sold 160 dollars each. The coins are engraved at the
back side with the patterns of bridge, unicorn, ox, butterfly, and
other auspicious symbols.
</P>
<P>
Around 12 a.m., approximately 2,000 people are still queuing
for the coins in two lines extending more than 600 meters, at one
of the outlets on the Gloucester Road in Wan Chai. According to
one of a dozen policeman who were maintaining order at the site,
the buyers have kept joining the lines since early morning but
they are in good order.
</P>
<P>
On June 22, the subway authority in Hong Kong offered a million
commemorative subway tickets, which can be used for an unlimited
inner city subway train trip on July 1, the day Hong Kong will
return to the embrace of the motherland. All the tickets were sold
out on that day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
