<HEADLINE> 2.84 Million Students to Take National Entrance Exam to College </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Over 2.84 million people have
applied to take the national college entrance exam this year,
180,000 more than 1996, and at least one out of every three
applicants will be enrolled by a college or university this autumn.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the State Education Commission (SEC) said here
today that China's 1,035 colleges and universities plan to enroll
1.01 million freshmen this year. This means that 45,000 more
people than the previous year will be able to go to college.
</P>
<P>
This year's three-day exam will be given from July 6 to 8, and
final results will be available in late July. Those who pass the
exam will be eligible for college admission in August.
</P>
<P>
Starting from the 1997 academic year, which begins in August,
all Chinese college students will be required to pay part of their
college tuition fees, which prior to 1994 were completely covered
by the government.
</P>
<P>
Tuition-free schooling will still be available to students
attending colleges and universities with specialities in
education, agriculture, forestry, public securities and geological
prospecting.
</P>
<P>
Colleges and universities that are authorized to enroll
students from Hong Kong, Macao, Taiwan and among overseas Chinese
gave their entrance exams from June 23 to 25. More than 1,200
students from these regions took the exam. Testing sites were in
Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Xiamen, Hong Kong and Macao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
