<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Condemns U.S. pro-Israeli Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign Minister
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said today the United States is only
subjecting herself to more global criticism if the Clinton
administration adopts the congressional resolution endorsing the
shift of Israel's capital to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem issue is a crucial one and a key subject in the
talks between Israel and Palestine for peace in West Asia,
Abdullah told reporters after meeting his Greek counterpart
Theodoros Pangalos who arrived here today for a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said being the mediating country, the U.S. should
accept as incumbent upon her to the play the role sincerely,
objectively and impartially.
</P>
<P>
"America should not be seen as being too pro-Israel... although
we know in many matters, the U.S. is indeed bias to the Israelis
and that the American pro-Israeli policy is a strong policy," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said Malaysia would persist in opposing the impending
shift of the Israeli capital from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem and would
pressure President Bill Clinton not to endorse the congressional
bill.
</P>
<P>
"We don't see how the shift can bring about anything good, but
instead will only cause a backlash of protests in various forms
especially from the Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC). In
fact even non-OIC members understand that it would be improper for
the U.S. to take such an action," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said the OIC would re-emphasize the protest at its
upcoming summit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
