<HEADLINE> Kenya-Zambia Row on Landing Rights Deepens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A protracted dispute over flights
scheduling and Kenya Airways' landing rights in Zambia has
deepened following the failure of the second meeting to resolve
the crisis between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yewondwossen Mengistu, the managing director of
Aero Zambia, has threatened to take the row to the International
Civil Aviation Organization in Montreal, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Mengistu, also the leader of the Zambian negotiation team,
said he had expected to find an agreement that would have
facilitated the sharing of revenue on the disputed flights but
found the Kenyan side had not changed its stance.
</P>
<P>
In response, the Zambian delegation insisted its ground not to
allow Kenya Airways to resume the two extra flights on the
Nairobi-Lusaka route until the matter was resolved.
</P>
<P>
The dispute stems from the cancellation of two Kenya Airways
flights to Lusaka on Mondays and Thursdays and the withdrawal of
landing rights for Kenya's flights by the Zambian authorities.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Airways is accused of having paralleled its flights to
those of Aero Zambia, Zambia's designated airline.
</P>
<P>
Air travel bilateral agreement between the two countries
allows three frequencies for each country but provides for an
extra frequency if the need arises.
</P>
<P>
Mengistu said his company did not mind Kenya Airway's flying
to Zambia so long as it is not on the days that it has flights.
</P>
<P>
He said his company's demand is that if it has to have flights
on the same day with Kenya Airways, then the two sides share
revenue equally.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Airways was said to have offered to compensate Aero
Zambia with 1,562.50 U.S. Dollars per flight but this was
rejected outright.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Aero Zambia maintained that it could only accept a
minimum compensation of some 3,500 Dollars per flight for Mondays
and Thursdays by the Kenya Airways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
