<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special Committee Established For Basic Law Implementation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature today
approved the establishment of a special committee to work for the
smooth implementation of the Basic Law -- the mini-constitution
for Hong Kong after the territory returns to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The Committee for the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (CBLHKSAR), which will begin to work on July
1 and is directly under the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, is comprised of 12 members, half of them from
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Xiang Chunyi, who is currently deputy director of the
Commission of Legislative Affairs of the NPC Standing Committee,
will head the new committee. The committee's vice chairman is
Hong Kong business tycoon Wong Po-yan, who also chairs the Hong
Kong Airport Authority and the Hong Kong One-Country-Two-Systems
Economic Research Center.
</P>
<P>
Both Xiang and Wong, along with some other committee members,
participated in the drafting of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The new committee's responsibilities include making suggestions
and offering ideas for any revision and amendment of the Basic Law
in the future. The NPC Standing Committee will consult the
committee before it gives interpretations regarding the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, the NPC Standing Committee can
return laws made by Hong Kong legislature when it considers the
laws are not in conformity with the provisions of the Basic
Law. However, the Standing Committee will listen to opinions of
the Basic Law Committee prior to the return.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee has the power to add or delete from
the list of national laws applied in Hong Kong, as included in
Appendix 3 of the Basic Law. The new committee can offer
suggestions for changing items on the list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
