<HEADLINE> Kohl: Euro Delay to Harm Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today
warned the German parliament that delay or failure of the single
European currency, the euro, would cost Germany dearly, and pledged
the on-time launch of euro in 1999.
</P>
<P>
He told the Bundestag, the lower house: "I am certain that ... the
euro will be introduced as planned, punctually on January 1, 1999,
meeting the full Maastricht criteria."
</P>
<P>
Delay or failure of the euro would harm exports, investment and
jobs, said Kohl in his speech.
</P>
<P>
"Those who call for delaying the euro must know that a delay could
end up being forever, we cannot... afford this," he noted.
</P>
<P>
In Germany, some politicians, such as Bavaria state premier
Edmund Stoiber, who is a member of the Bavarian sister party of
Kohl's Christian Democratic Uinon (CDU), has urged delaying the
euro if Germany fails to meet the membership criteria demanding
budget deficit under 3 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) and
public debt under 60 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Germany has failed to meet the requirements over recent years
and most experts believed it would fail again this year. In May
1998, the European Union (EU) is to conclude from the 1997 full
data to see which countries qualify for the euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
