<HEADLINE> Kenya Remains Ban on Wildlife Hunting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government will
maintain the ban on hunting in the country's parks, Kenyan
Tourism and Wildlife Minister Protus Momanyi has said.
</P>
<P>
Momanyi said that lifting of the ban would create a demand for
trade in game products, leading to uncontrolled killing of wild
animals, according to the "Daily Nation" today.
</P>
<P>
"Before the government imposed a ban on hunting, there was
wanton killing of wild animals by poachers. White rhinos were
almost becoming extinct, forcing the government to import some
from South Africa", the Kenyan minister said when receiving the Dutch
Ambassador Ruud Treffers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
There were 130,000 rhinos in Kenya's parks in early 1960s but
poaching and uncontrolled hunting had reduced the rhino
population to less than 11,000 by the late 1970s, he cited.
</P>
<P>
The population of elephants in the national parks in the
eastern African country now stood at 26,000, up from 20,000
before the ban.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is among the countries who contested a request by some
southern African countries to have the ban on ivory trade lifted
at the recent Convention on International Trade in Endangered
Species in Harare, Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
