<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" Is Long-Term Policy for Hong Kong: Noted Figures (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The policy of "one country, two
systems" is bound to succeed and will remain unchanged for a long
time in Hong Kong, according to local noted figures.
</P>
<P>
With only four days away before Hong Kong returns to China on
July 1, the phrase "one country, two systems" has become one of
the best-known and most-frequently-used one in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Local media described this policy as the "inevitable choice to
realize China's reunification", while many people across the world
praised it for setting an example in solving problems left over
from history through peaceful negotiations.
</P>
<P>
But it is unprecedented in the world history that two different
social systems can co-exist in one sovereign country. Some people
are wondering whether the principle of "one country, two systems"
will remain unchanged for a long time.
</P>
<P>
In answering the question, a dozen noted figures from various
walks of life in Hong Kong expressed confidence and optimism in
recent interviews with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that "one country, two systems" is not an expedient
measure, but a lasting policy decision based on the reality of
Hong Kong and China's interior areas.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that the interior areas, which are now in a
modernization process, need Hong Kong as a unique bridge linking
them with the outside world, while Hong Kong's sustained
prosperity and stability also require interior areas enjoying
long-term stability and scoring sustained economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The economic miracle that Hong Kong has performed over the past
two decades and the tremendous achievements that China's interior
areas have scored since initiating the policy of the reform and
opening up serve as the most convincing fact, they said.
</P>
<P>
Tsang Hin-chi, chairman of the Hong Kong Chinese General
Chamber of Commerce, recalled that when the question of Hong
Kong's return to China was first raised in the early 1980s, some
people in Hong Kong and other parts of the world expressed worries
and doubts about Hong Kong's future, arguing that Hong Kong's
economic prosperity would be "ruined" after the handover.
</P>
<P>
"But their doubts and worries were gradually dispelled by the
great concept of 'one country, two systems' put forward by Deng
Xiaoping, and the prospects of Hong Kong began to become
increasingly brighter," he said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the current prosperity of Hong Kong to the hard
work of the Hong Kong people and Hong Kong's unique economic
operational mechanism, as well as the "China factor".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" Is Long-Term Policy for Hong Kong: Noted Figures (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tam Yiu-chung, vice-chairman of the Hong Kong Federation of
Trade Unions and member of the Executive Council of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), shared Tsang's opinion.
</P>
<P>
"One important factor contributing to Hong Kong's economic
recovery after a period of adjustment is the backing of the strong
motherland," he said. "If the current situation of stability and
development in the interior areas continues, it will contribute
more to making sure that 'one country, two systems' will remain
unchanged for a long time."
</P>
<P>
Nellie Fong Wong Kut-man, chairman of the Executive Committee
of the Better Hong Kong Foundation, said that as an international
financial, trade, shipping, information and tourism center, Hong
Kong has an effective free economic mechanism. It is this
mechanism that has enabled Hong Kong to become one of the most
appealing places to investors and business people across the
world.
</P>
<P>
She said that retaining the existing systems will not only
ensure Hong Kong's long-term prosperity and stability, but also
build a bridge between China's interior areas and the global
market.
</P>
<P>
"Only by preserving the existing systems will Hong Kong be able
to remain vibrant and competitive," she noted. "A Hong Kong
without vigor or competitiveness would not be what Hong Kong
people want to see and would also be useless to China's interior
areas."
</P>
<P>
"I am sure the central government of the People's Republic of
China, which can manage 1.2 billion people successfully, must have
a better understanding of this than I do," said Fong, who is a
member of the HKSAR Executive Council.
</P>
<P>
Many business people in Hong Kong like to say that the economic
and trade relations between Hong Kong and China's interior areas
are "as close as lips and teeth".
</P>
<P>
"With the backing of China's vast interior areas, Hong Kong has
achieved a fast and successful industrial restructuring," said
Michael Sze, executive director of the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council.
</P>
<P>
He said that the need of the interior areas for funds for
economic construction has stimulated the growth of Hong Kong's
financial market, and trade with the interior areas has spurred
the development of Hong Kong's trade-oriented service sector.
</P>
<P>
"The interior areas are the rear for Hong Kong industries, and
have also made plenty of investment in Hong Kong," he added.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that beyond 1997, in accordance with the policy of
"one country, two systems", the economic and trade relations
between China's interior areas and Hong Kong will be further
enhanced, injecting an "enormous impetus" into economic growth of
both regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS more to follow hkhk --"One country, Two Systems" Is Long-Term Policy for Hong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Eddy S.H. Li, president of the Hong Kong Economic and Trade
Association, shared his view. He said, "The market in the interior
areas will be open wider to Hong Kong, bringing enormous business
opportunities to the city after its return to the motherland."
</P>
<P>
Li also asked the Hong Kong business community to be aware of
the challenges faced by its processing industry in the interior
areas which are readjusting their policy on utilizing foreign
investment and giving overseas businessmen the same treatment as
their counterparts in the interior areas.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, the redoubled effort by the interior areas
to open to the outside world will push Hong Kong companies to more
fierce competition in expanding their business there.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" and a "high degree of
autonomy" constitute a basis on which the "one country, two
systems" policy will remain unchanged for a long time.
</P>
<P>
"The central government has stated that it will act as a
"goalkeeper" for the "one country, two systems, and Hong Kong
people should have a correct understanding of this," said Sze
Chi-qing, another Hong Kong business tycoon.
</P>
<P>
Sze, also an advisor on Hong Kong and SAR affairs, said that in
their speeches, Deng Xiaoping and Chinese leaders of the third
generation have repeatedly emphasized that Hong Kong's current
social and economic systems will remain unchanged, its legal
system will not change by and large, and its status as a free port
and an international trade and financial center will not change
either.
</P>
<P>
This will be beneficial to Hong Kong and the whole of China as
well, he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, Sze added the "one country, two systems" means that
Hong Kong will maintain its capitalist system, whereas the
interior areas of China will continue to practice the socialist
system."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One country, Two Systems" Is Long-Term Policy for Hong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since "one country, two systems" and "Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong" is an unprecedented practice, it is
understandable that some people may have worries.
</P>
<P>
Woo Chia-wei, president of the Hong Kong University of Science
and Technology, said, "As the times are changing, many
unprecedented undertakings can be put into practice in a bold,
prudent and earnest manner, so long as the general public reaches
a consensus. Only this way can the human society advance."
</P>
<P>
On the question of Hong Kong's return to China, "one country,
two systems" is a principle which is acceptable to all sides and
has gone through preparations for a long time," said Woo.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been ruled by an European country several
thousand miles away in the past 156 years, and therefore, many
people in Hong Kong have a "marginal concept", Woo said. So many
people in Hong Kong have accepted "two systems," but are
unfamiliar with "one country".
</P>
<P>
He said, "I don't think the Hong Kong people should doubt
whether the "one country, two systems" will remain unchanged for a
long time. Instead, they should think carefully about whether they
will be able to have a good understanding of the essence of the
'one country, two systems' within a short period of time."
</P>
<P>
Lee Chark-tim, president of Hong Kong Federation of Trade
Unions, pointed out, "Hong Kong people will dispel their worries
as long as they come to understand the principle of 'one country,
two systems', 'Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong' and a high
degree of autonomy, and see with their own eyes that Hong Kong's
social and economic systems and their lifestyles will not change,
and that its existing laws will remain unchanged by and large."
</P>
<P>
"The 'one country, two systems' principle has become the source
of hopes for the Hong Kong people to look into the future," said
Sze Cheung-pang, a member of the National Committee of Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC).
</P>
<P>
"We should entirely accept the principle and participate in
implementing it as well," said Sze, an influential businessman in
Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
