<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Official Highly Evaluates Hang Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 27 (Xinhua) -- "In getting Hong Kong Back,
they (China) have reversed a historic injustice," Reuven Merhav,
a senior Israeli China hand, told The Jerusalem Post.
</P>
<P>
He made the comment in an interview with the English newspaper
a few days before China is to resume the exercise of sovereignty
over Hong Kong on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Merhav, who served as director-general of the Israeli Foreign
Ministry, visited China in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Despite predictions of mass flight from Hong Kong, the
population has remained in place and apartment values have gone
up, he said.
</P>
<P>
Merhav said that he believes China will also achieve
reunification with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish community in Hong Kong has increased in size in
recent years and it is estimated that there are 3,000 Jews
residing in Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
Merhav said that the handover will go far toward hastening
China's emergence as a world economic power. "China has foreign
reserves of about 115 billion U.S. dollars and Hong Kong has
reserves of about 70 billion. Together, that's almost equal to
Japan's," he said.
</P>
<P>
Merhav noted that Hong kong is the engine driving the economic
dynamics of south China.
</P>
<P>
As a management and banking center and transportation hub, Hong
Kong has increasingly shifted production over the years to the
nearby Chinese provinces, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to view the whole region, including south China and
Taiwan, as one economic unit of 150 million people with Hong Kong
at the center," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
