<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS May Prefer Military Solution to S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Military action to oust Sierra
Leone's military junta may be a choice by foreign ministers from
west African countries who began a meeting on Thursday in
Conakry, Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) discussed the deteriorating situation in Sierra
Leone and ways of rectifying it, press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The military junta seized power through a coup on May 25 which
overthrew the elected civilian government led by ousted President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The coup has suffered wide condemnation from the international
community. A series of diplomatic talks for a peaceful settlement
of the crisis in Sierra Leone followed unsuccessful military
efforts by the ECOWAS peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG to
restore the toppled legistimate government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, coup leader Major Johnny Paul Koroma expressed his
readiness on Wednesday that he would allow Kabbah, who is
reportedly on exile in Guinea, to return as long as he stopped
"misleading" the international community.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the nation, Koroma also diclosed he would
soon announce the composition of his new government and a
"timetable for a proper return to civil rule".
</P>
<P>
Against the background, ECOWAS foreign ministers held their
first meeting since the May 25 coup to probe ways for settling
the crisis in Sierra Leone, which is a member of the sub-regional
organization.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Salim Ahmed Salim, secretary-general of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) reiterated at the meeting
OAU's support to "any method that would restore the legitimate
government in Sierra Leone".
</P>
<P>
Though no communique was announced after Thursday's meeting,
there seems to be strong likelihood that ECOWAS foreign ministers
may finally recommend military action against the Sierra Leonan
military junta to reinstate Kabbah, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Except Ghana, which was described as a "lone voice" at the
meeting, other members agreed on a military option since
diplomatic moves had not succeeded in forcing Koroma's Armed
Forces Revolutionary Council to step down.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, Ghana's deputy foreign minister visited Freetown
with the information that ECOWAS had not agreed to oust by force
the coupists.
</P>
<P>
The visit was reported to give confidence to Koroma's military
government.
</P>
<P>
But at the end of Thursday's ECOWAS foreign ministers meeting,
a source was quoted as saying that the mood at the meeting
indicated an "imminent military intervention".
</P>
<P>
In his first public statement on the May 25 takeover, ECOWAS
Chairman, Nigeria's head of state General Sani Abacha also called
for immediate steps to restore peace, order and legitimacy in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the meeting, Abacha said if the situation in Sierra
Leone was not carefully managed, it might retard the peace process in
Liberia and threaten the stability of Guinea, both immediate neighbors
of that country.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony the same day to launch a new book in Abuja,
capital of Nigeria, Abacha also stoutly defended Nigeria's
current role in Sierra Leone, saying it is not an interference.
</P>
<P>
Responsibility is placed on Nigeria for ensuring the stability
of the sub-region, he said.
</P>
<P>
As a sub-regional power, Nigeria is the main contributor of ECOMOG
which has been operating in Liberia for some seven years. It also has
a contingent in Freetown for military training mission under an
agreement signed with Kabbah's government.
</P>
<P>
The leading role of Nigeria in ECOMOG operation in Sierra
Leone has been much criticized by the military authorities of
that country who said the country opposed any foreign
interference of its internal affairs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
