<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 09:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Minister Says Mideast Peace Is Dying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz has stressed that the Middle East peace process is "dying"
due to policy of right-wing Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu, Beirut's Arabic daily An-Nahar reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz made the statement in a speech addressed Thursday
evening to a forum here under the title of "Lebanon, situation of
the Arab-Israeli peace and its horizon," according to the
largest-circulated conservative newspaper in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"The peace process is dying, and it not only needs a re-push
but also needs a re-creation," said Boueiz.
</P>
<P>
He noted that during the time of former Israeli (Labour) Prime
Ministers Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres and despite a stalemate
in the peace talks, there was still a feeling that the
circumstances would improve and the peace negotiations would go
forward.
</P>
<P>
But after Netanyahu came to power in May 1996, "the things
changed and a new stage came, that is the stage of destroying the
peace process," the foreign minister added.
</P>
<P>
After taking office, the Israeli hard-line Likud Party leader
immediately imposed his own radical policy, known as the "security
for peace" policy, destroying basis of the peace process under the
formula of "land for peace" advocated by the Labor government,
Boueiz said.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz said the U.S. government's policy was characterized by
an "absolute" commitment to Israeli suggestions.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Israel on the one hand and Syria and
Lebanon on the other have been suspended since February 1996.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, Israel has been occupying a 1,100-square-kilometer
strip of land in South Lebanon, using the so-called "security
zone" to ward off cross-border guerilla attacks on its northern
settlements.
</P>
<P>
The "security zone" is patrolled by 1,500 Israeli troops and by
the South Lebanese Army (SLA), an Israeli-financed 2,500-strong
Christian militia.
</P>
<P>
Israel has demanded that SLA militia be integrated into the
Lebanese army as part of the security arrangements between the
Lebanese and Israeli governments, which will ensure the Israeli
withdrawal from the "security zone." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
