<HEADLINE> Uganda No Longer Among Poorest Ten </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is no longer among world's
ten poorest nations, reported the local daily " The New Vision"
today.
</P>
<P>
The latest World Bank report issued Wednesday was quoted as
saying Uganda's per capita income has risen for the sixth
consecutive year to 240 U.S. Dollars and for the first time in
two decades the country is not among the poorest nations in the
world.
</P>
<P>
It said Mozambique remain the world's poorest country with a
per capita income of only 80 dollars. The second is Ethiopia with
a per capita income of 100 dollars while Tanzania is with a per
capita income of 120 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report praised Uganda for the way it has tried to tackle
corruption and to encourage non-governmental organizations to
deliver social services in areas where it is unable to.
</P>
<P>
Corruption is a 'cancer' eating away many poor countries, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the key issue is to encourage
competition. It also says that only in a good policy environment will
foreign aid have any impact on growth.
</P>
<P>
It said 16 of the world's poorest countries remain in sub-Sahara
Africa while 12 of the richest 20 are in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The richest country in the world, in terms of per capita
income is Switzerland with 40,630 dollars followed by Japan with
39,640 dollars and Norway with 31,250 dollars, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Arrests 72 for Illegal Military Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Uganda government troops arrested
72 young men and killed another two in north-western district of
Arua for illegal military training, "The New Vision" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Security sources in the district said yesterday that army have
rounded up the group in a village near Uganda-Congo border. Two
training officers have been killed as they tried to escape.
</P>
<P>
They were lured by some remnants of the West Nile Bank Front
(WNBF), a crippled rebel group based in the north-west.
</P>
<P>
Recent reports said some WNBF remnants joined Allied
Democratic Forces (ADF) acting in the west.
</P>
<P>
Security sources hold that the WNBF remnants trained the 72
youths for ADF.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the government troops of Congo
arrested yesterday four ADF rebels in a village near Congo-Uganda
border. ADF rebels acting in Bundibugyo district, western Uganda,
were fleeing to Congo in small groups, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
The four arrestees were a part of them. An earlier report said
ADF has a camp in Congo near Uganda-Congo border.
</P>
<P>
ADF's main forces are operating in western Kasese district. The
rebel group sent some 250 men to Boundibugyo to develop a reliable
food sources on June 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
