<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore, Qingdao Establish Direct Airlink </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Singapore and Qingdao city of
Shandong province, China, established direct airlink as the
inaugural Air China flight from Qingdao arrived in Changi Airport
late last night, carrying among the passengers a 16-member
delegation from Shandong province to Singapore for an official
visit till next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Trade Development Board and Air China said in a
joint statement here today that this is currently the only direct
airlink between Singapore and Shandong province. It is also the
third international air route established by Qingdao city
following that with Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Air China's B767-200 airplane will operate on the
Singapore-Qingdao two-way air route and there will be on flight on
every Thursday from now till October 26 this year. Thereafter, the
number of flights will increase to two flights per week on every
Thursday and Sunday, Air China said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the significance of the direct Singapore-Qingdao
airlink, Tang Guan Seng, Senior Parliamentary Secretary and
Co-chairman of the Singapore-Shandong Business Council (SSBC),
said that "the new direct airlink will further improve
communication between Singapore and Shandong."
</P>
<P>
"It adds impetus to commercial and tourism cooperation between
the two areas and underscores the degree of importance Shandong
attaches to Singapore's trade and investment," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member delegation from Shandong, led by Song Fatang,
executive vice governor of Shandong province and co-chairman of
the SSBC, will attend the fourth council meeting of the SSBC to
discuss current areas of cooperation such as manpower training
programs, enterprise development and tripartite cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
