<HEADLINE> Lusaka Reduces Property Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Lusaka City Council has
reduced property rate by 50 percent with immediate effect to
attract more investors, Times of Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted the council's Public Relations
Manager Daniel Msoka as saying here Tuesday that the council may
reward more tax relief to property owners if the measures to
broaden income succeed.
</P>
<P>
"We have reduced rate from 0.0105 to 0.0050 in a Kwacha with
immediate effect. This means that property owners will pay half
from whatever amount they owe the council," he said.
</P>
<P>
Msoka said property owners are supposed to settle the money
they owe the city council within 14 days of receipt of the
notices. Failure to do so bailiffs will move in.
</P>
<P>
But another local newspaper, Zambia Daily Mail, reported that
the council reduced the rate following wide spread complaints
from business houses and the general public.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Msoka as saying that the reduction will create a
deficit of 3.6 billion Kwacha (about 2.8 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
In order to offset the deficit, the council will soon embark
on a supplementary property roll to catch up with an upswing in
the level of development EEince 1995 when the current main
valuation roll was done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
