<HEADLINE> Dutch Overseas Chinese Celebrate HK's Return to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch capital city of
Amsterdam was full of joy Thursday with celebrations organized by
overseas Chinese in the Netherlands to mark Hong Kong's return to
its motherland on July 1.
</P>
<P>
A celebration gathering, held in the city's New Market Square,
was attended by more than 1,000 overseas Chinese from all over the
country.
</P>
<P>
"I have never seen such a grand gathering organized by the
Dutch overseas Chinese," said an old Chinese businessman living in
Amsterdam. "As an overseas Chinese, I'm very proud and feel so
lucky to be a witness of Hong Kong's return to my motherland after
more than 150 years."
</P>
<P>
At a forum held in the city's famous Chinese restaurant Sea
Palace, more than 50 attendants representing the 100,000 overseas
Chinese living in the Netherlands spoke out freely on the return
of Hong Kong to China, which has drawn worldwide attention in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Hu Zhiguang, a leading person of Dutch overseas Chinese and
president of the Federation of Associations of Overseas Chinese in
Europe, said Hong Kong's return was a firm indication of the
increasing power of China, which also provided powerful backing
for overseas Chinese.
</P>
<P>
During a celebration in Amsterdam's RAI theater, Chinese
Ambassador to the Netherlands Zhu Manli said that the Chinese
people are very grateful to Deng Xiaoping who had pioneered the
"one country, two systems" principle, which has made it possible
the smooth return of Hong Kong to China.
</P>
<P>
She expressed confidence that Hong Kong would be more
prosperous after its return to China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
