<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk-Director of Audit Vows to Serve Hong Kong Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 53-year-old Mr. Chan is not only a celebrity but also a
pride of Hong Kong, since he is the first Chinese to be promoted
to the post of Director of Audit, a key post in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
As a major commercial hub, Hong Kong has always attached great
importance to auditing, setting up an audit department as early as
in 1844. However, all of Chan's 20 predecessors were foreign
nationals.
</P>
<P>
He would never have dared to dream of his promotion if not for
the return of Hong Kong to its motherland, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I treasure the opportunity of service as Director of Audit. I
have been trying to prove by my work that a Chinese can be a good
leader of the audit department," Chan said.
</P>
<P>
Like most principal officials of the current HK government, Mr.
Chan will retain his post, which he assumed in 1995, in the future
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) government. "The
return of Hong Kong to the motherland gives me an opportunity to
continue to serve Hong Kong, and I'll try my uttermost to do my
work well", he said.
</P>
<P>
He has a demanding job. It is the responsibility of his
department to ensure that financial and accounting records of
public or semi-public funds comply with commonly-accepted
accounting standards.
</P>
<P>
The department also acts as a watchdog against waste and lack
of efficiency on the part of government departments.
</P>
<P>
Since auditing is meant to find and expose problems, it cannot
avoid offending people, he said. "Ever since I began working for
the Audit Department nearly 30 years ago, I have abided by a set
of ethical standards, that is, to have enterprise, to have moral
integrity and to adhere to principle," he said.
</P>
<P>
An important thing he has done since assuming his current post,
he said, is the hiring of professional consultants to solve
problems that require special knowledge. In the past, some of
these problems had to be left unsolved owing to their complexity
defying a solution.
</P>
<P>
On his plan of work for the HKSAR government, Chan said he will
push for accelerating audit-related legislation and enhance
exchanges with developed countries and the audit departments of
China's interior areas.
</P>
<P>
"Auditing should be done in a more in-depth, extensive and
objective manner so as to save every penny of tax-payers' money
and ensure that the government work with greater efficiency," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
