<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law Professionals Confident about HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
They unanimously regard the Basic Law as a cornerstone of the
"one country, two systems" concept and said that it provides a
very pragmatic framework and a favorable environment for the
development of the future Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR).
</P>
<P>
Lau Hon Chuen, a member of the Provisional Legislative Council
(PLS) of the Hong Kong SAR, said that the Basic Law is effective
in implementing "one country, two systems" policy, since it
generously grants a high degree of autonomy for the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
Besides, what the Chinese government has done in handling Hong
Kong affairs over recent years is an evidence that it has taken
the Basic Law very seriously, Lau noted.
</P>
<P>
In his view, the drafting of the Basic Law itself was a
successful rehearsal for the smooth implementation of "one
country, two systems" policy, whose curtain will be formally
raised with China's resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
As an example of the unprecedented, arduous and extensive
cooperation between Hong Kong and China's interior area, the Basic
Law drafting did manifest as well as generate the key elements
that the success of the reunification model requires pragmatism,
procedural rationality and democratic communication.
</P>
<P>
After an analysis on amending and retaining the existing laws
in Hong Kong in accordance with the Basic Law, Albert H.Y. Chen,
dean of the Faculty of Law of the University of Hong Kong noted
that in terms of civil and commercial laws, some areas of public
law, or even in the field of human rights, the original laws of
Hong Kong may be considered as just as specified in the Joint
Declaration -- "remaining basically unchanged". He said the Laws
of the Hong Kong SAR will protect the rights and interests of all
individuals and legal persons. Therefore, he added, he fully
confides in the future of Hong's legal system.
</P>
<P>
Elsie Leung, secretary of Justice of the HKSAR, said it is a
period of excitement to witness Hong Kong's return to China and
see a city under British colonial rule turn into the Special
Administrative Region of China.
</P>
<P>
According to Leung, the Chief Executive's Office is racing
against time in making preparations to set up the Hong Kong SAR
and one of the goals in such preparations is aimed to avoid
loopholes in the field of legislation.
</P>
<P>
She acknowledged that redoubled, diversified efforts should be
made for the use of the Chinese language in court and in the
application of international human rights law in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth C K Chow, a barrister-at-law of Hong Kong, said that
the courts of Hong Kong SAR are vested with a pivotal role which
will be enshrined in history, namely, to carry forward the
original laws of Hong Kong into the era of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
According to Chow, who is also a member of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), the stability and prosperity of Hong Kong
after its return to the motherland is inseparable from the
preservation of the legal system previously practised in Hong
Kong.
Moreover, he said, in the wake of the successful establishment of
the Court of Final Appeal, the future judicial system of the Hong
Kong SAR will surely be able to aspire to a much better outlook,
and a much better tomorrow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
