<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Promises Actions to Advance Sustainable Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today told the U.N. Earth Summit that the United States will take
actions to deal with climate change and advance sustainable
development both at home and in the world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 19th Special Session of the General Assembly of
the United Nations, also known as the Earth Summit 5, Clinton said
the U.S. will provide 1 billion U.S. dollars in assistance over
the next five years to help developing countries reduce greenhouse
gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
The funds will go to programs that support energy efficiency,
develop alternative energy sources and improve resource management
to promote growth that does not adversely affect the climate, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The president said the U.S. will continue to encourage private
investment that meets environmental standards. The U.S. overseas
private investment corporation will now require that its projects
adhere to new and strengthened environmental guidelines.
</P>
<P>
At home, Clinton said, the U.S. must unleash more of the
creative power of the American people to meet the challenge of
climate change.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government will work with business communities to
install solar panels on the roofs of 1 million houses around the
country by 2010 to help turn down the earth's temperature.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been under attacks at the special session
for refusing to set targets to cut global warming and for reducing
funds for ecological projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
