<HEADLINE> Israel Arrests 500 Palestinian Suspects in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli security forces have
arrested 500 Palestinians suspected of having links to terror
organizations in a major crackdown on terrorism, Israel Radio
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The crackdown came after the discovery of a time bomb on the
crowded Tel Aviv beach last week which was believed to be planted
by terrorists. A thief stole the bag containing the bomb, but he
reported to the police when he found out it was actually a
tickling timer bomb.
</P>
<P>
Tel Aviv police have since heightened security alert along the
beach and other places of entertainment in order to prevent new
terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
Israel radio said that the 500 Palestinian suspects are
believed to be linked to the anti-Israeli Islamic militant
organizations, such as the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas),
Islamic Jihad and Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Security forces continued to warn the public that the
possibility of new terror attacks still exist, adding they are
fighting a daily struggle to thwart any new attempts to penetrate
by Palestinian suspects.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, Tel Aviv police will increase security
alert along the beach area and other places of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli police have arrested Ahmed Ali Kaabneh, a
Beduin shepherd who was accused of murdering two Israeli girls on
April 24 during a hiking tour in the Wadi Kelt along the
Jerusalem-Jericho highway.
</P>
<P>
Police said that the motive for the murders was nationalistic,
and Kaabneh murdered the girls in an attempt to steal weapons from
the victims who in fact carried none.
</P>
<P>
Following the arrest of Kaabneh, the Council of Jewish
Settlers in the Palestinian territories demanded that all the
Beduin living in the Judean Sesert be removed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
