<HEADLINE> Booming Trade in Harbin Brings in More Russian Businessmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of Russian
businessmen shuttling between Russia and Harbin has brought
millions of yuan-worth of sales orders to Harbin, the capital of
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
While most of these businessmen from Russia and other central
Asian countries are dealing in small commodities, their total
purchases in a major local marketplace reached 500 million yuan
last year.
</P>
<P>
The daily transactions of the Harbin Non-Governmental Trade
Market have now reached 1.5 million yuan. The figure was less than
300,000 yuan just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
The market covers an area of 30,000 square meters, and is used
as a sales base by 3,000 independently-operating Chinese
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Local sources say that at least 500 Russian businessmen visit
the market every morning, and as many as 1,000 on Thursdays and
Fridays when an express train makes stopover in the city.
</P>
<P>
Some state-owned firms, foreign-funded enterprises and private
companies have been involved in the market, dealing directly with
the buyers of their goods.
</P>
<P>
Products made in the Republic of Korea, the United States and
Australia are also sold in the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Per Capita GDP to Surpass 3,000 Dollars This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The per capita GDP (gross
domestic product) of residents in Shanghai, China's largest trade
and financial city, will exceed 3,000 US dollars this year,
according to recent statistics.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents the city's great progress in
industrialization, and has attracted the attention of both
economists and government officials.
</P>
<P>
Economists here have been advising the government on ways to
deal with the challenges facing the city's burgeoning economy.
</P>
<P>
"This marks a new starting point for Shanghai's economy, and
new changes will take place in the city's industrial structure and
methods of economic growth," said Lu Deming, director of the
Economic Research Center of Fudan University.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that the output value of the service industry will
increase from today's 42 percent to half of the city's total GDP
by the year of 2000, due to the growth of capital-intensive
industries.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the Shanghai market will open even wider, and the
market competition will be tougher than before, he added.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will be built into one of China's modern manufacturing
industry centers, and the city's finance, trade and transportation
industries will also develop rapidly, said Zhang Zhongli, chairman
of the Shanghai Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
An international seminar sponsored by the local government and
academic institutions was recently held to discuss the city's GDP
growth.  
</P>
