<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Sets up Export Promotion Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has
decided to form a high-powered export promotion board in a bid to
give a major thrust to exports, the newspaper National Herald
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Prime minister Inder Kumar Gujral announced the decision on
Thursday at a meeting convened by him in view of the massive slow
down in the country's exports in 1996-97 and a 10 percent decline
in exports in April 1997, the first month of the current fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
During his interactions with trade and industry
representatives, Gujral said the new board will help resolve the
inter-ministerial problems related to exports.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister took a serious view of the sharp fall in the
exports and took some other on-the-spot decisions on exports.
</P>
<P>
The board, headed by the cabinet secretary, will include
secretaries of the ministries of commerce, finance, textile
industry, surface transport and electronics. Secretary is the
highest ranking civil servant in India.
</P>
<P>
The decision on export promotion board was made in response to
suggestions from Indian exporters that a single window
institutional mechanism should be set up to facilitate the
country's exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
