<HEADLINE> Huzhou Buys Back Land at Big Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Huzhou city government has
paid 25 million yuan to buy back a piece of land in the downtown
area which had been sold to real estate developers, to build a
12,000-square-meter public park.
</P>
<P>
Huzhou, located in east China's Zhejiang Province, has been
known throughout the country's history for its rice
production. The city lies along the south bank of Taihu Lake, one
of the country's five major freshwater lakes.
</P>
<P>
The city's population has increased to 460,000 over the years
as a result of steady economic growth, and its total area covers
13 square km.
</P>
<P>
However, city fathers have always had trouble finding a good
place where the local residents can relax.
</P>
<P>
The land which had been purchased by developers was to be used
for office buildings in the city's central area.
</P>
<P>
The new park, which has been met with the enthusiasm of the
public, will feature fountains and artificial streams. 
</P>
