<HEADLINE> Manila Continues Military Operation Against MILF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government forces today
continued its hot-pursuit operations in central Mindanao in search
of Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebels, who took hostage
some 100 commuters in Kabacan, Cotabato province Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Cotabato quoted military spokesman Noel Detoyato
as saying that the government troops are conducting a no-let-up
operation in Kabacan, Pikit and Carmen towns since MILF rebels
took about 100 hostages early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Later Thursday, the government troops engaged the rebels in a
fierce battle in Kayaga, Kabacan to rescue the hostages, who were
passengers of buses and other vehicles that the MILF flagged down
in the area.
</P>
<P>
Four soldiers, four rebels and two hostages were killed in
Thursday's battle.
</P>
<P>
After the fighting, the MILF announced the postponement of its
peace talks with the government scheduled for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said only 45 hostages managed to escape Thursday
as MILF rebels fled to a nearby forest area.
</P>
<P>
"Some hostages might have escaped the fighting but they did not
manifest their names so we are searching for them to determine if
they're free or still being taken by the rebels," said Detoyato.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Defense Secretary Renato de Villa revealed Thursday
that more troops will be deployed in Central Mindanao to hunt the
hostage-takers.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, which rejected a Mindanao peace accord signed by the
government and the Moro National Liberation Front Last September,
is fighting for independence of Mindanao, the Southern
Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
