<HEADLINE> China Reports Good International Balance of Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- China achieved a good balance of
international payments in 1996, the State Administration of
Foreign Exchange has announced.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that the surplus under the current
account stood at 7.242 billion US dollars last year, which was on
top of a trade surplus of 19.535 billion US dollars, a favorable
balance of 2.129 billion US dollars in unrequited transfer and a
non-trade deficit of 14.422 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade rose 1.9 percent to 282.62 billion US dollars,
which broke down into 151.077 billion US dollars in exports and
131.542 billion US dollars in imports, up 1.6 percent and 4.8
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The positive balance under the capital account neared 40
billion US dollars last year. Of 69.721 billion US dollars in
capital inflow, direct investment accounted for 42.35 billion US
dollars, a rise of 12.23 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reserve assets went up by 31.65 billion US dollars,
which included an increase of 31.43 billion in foreign exchange,
32 million US dollars in special drawing rights and 188 million US
dollars in reserve positions on the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
</TEXT>
