<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A plan of the ruling United
Front government to raise the prices of gas and petroleum products
with immediate effect suffered a setback on Thursday as the
Congress Party refused to support the move, the Indian Express
said today.
</P>
<P>
Congress Party President Sitaram Kesri held an hour-long
close-door meeting with Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral on the
subject on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Kesri was assisted by the party's vice president Jitendra
Prasada and former External Affairs Minister Pranab Mukherjee.
</P>
<P>
While cautioning Gujral against any immediate increase in the
oil prices, Kesri said it would adversely affect the common man
and his party needs time to study the proposal.
</P>
<P>
The government intends to hike the oil prices to reduce the
rising deficit caused by subsidies to gas and petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
Reliable sources said the Gujral government has proposed a 6-
to 8-percent gas and diesel price hike to complete the reforms in
the oil sector.
</P>
<P>
Because the ruling United Front government needs outside
support in the parliament from the Congress Party, a panel
comprising Gujral and Kesri was formed in April for both sides to
coordinate on major decision-making.  
</P>
