<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Switches Topic as Gases Criticism Mounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- United States President
Bill Clinton tried hard today to shun criticism from his European
allies for failing to set clear targets for his country on cutting
greenhouse gases emissions.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 173-nation United Nations Earth Summit, Clinton
switched the topic and spared no efforts in stressing the
importance of sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
"Five years ago in Rio de Janeiro, the nations of the world
joined together around a simple but revolutionary proposition:
that today's progress must not come at tomorrow's expense," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Then focusing on the danger of greenhouse gases, he said if
pollution is not controlled, "scientists expect the seas to rise
two feet or more in the next century." That meant 9000 square
miles of Florida, Louisiana and other coastal areas would be
flooded, and 17 percent of Bangladesh lost.
</P>
<P>
The European Union proposes reducing greenhouse gases -- carbon
dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide -- by 15 percent below 1990
levels with a deadline of 2010.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure from big industry and Congress, Clinton refused
to commit to targets before December's global warming treaty
negotiations in Kyoto, Japan.
</P>
<P>
In order to sooth sore feelings among allies, he promised to
back tighter pollution limits on soot and smog in the United
States, the biggest polluter of the globe.
</P>
<P>
He called on government, university and private sector
scientists to develop new technologies to curb global warming.
</P>
<P>
He vowed that the U.S. will bring to the Kyoto conference in
December strong American commitments to realistic and binding
limits that will significantly reduce its emissions of greenhouse
gases.
</P>
<P>
The week-long summit, dubbed "Earth Summit Plus 5", aimed to
review progress since the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil
in 1992, when participating countries agreed to seek sustainable
development, or international economic growth with environmental
protection attached. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
