<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Ties between Inland Area and Hong Kong to Be Further Enhanced after Handover: Official(3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"If there is any change after the handover, it will be that
Hong Kong's position and role will be further enhanced," he said.
</P>
<P>
An explained that foreign trade volume in China's inland areas
will hit 400 billion US dollars by the end of this century, and
the areas will become a huge market in need of more than 700
billion US dollars worth of commodities in years up to 2000.
</P>
<P>
All this presents great potentials for further trade and
eocnomic cooperations and exchanges between the inland areas and
Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
An predicts that the growth of trade volume will be accompanied
by the improvement of the commodity mix.
</P>
<P>
Major inland exports to Hong Kong will shift to finished
products and semi-finished products from traditional items such as
food and raw materials, while more technology- and
capital-intensive goods will to the inland areas from Hong Kong,
An noted.
</P>
<P>
The assistant minister also said that large and medium-sized
cities, as well as western and central provinces in the inland
areas are expected to emerge as hot investment spots for Hong Kong
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
And the exchanges in the service sector will anticipate a
boost, An pointed out, adding that the service industry already
accounts for 83 percent of Hong Kong's economy and its further
growth will constitute a positive effect on the development
of the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The inland areas also aspire to do their share to upgrade the
infrastructure in Hong Kong and boost its economy through
contracting projects and labor exports based on the region's
actual demand, An explained.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the management and development of the
inland-financed companies in Hong Kong, An said that they should
abide by as well as be protected by the laws and regulations in
the region. In other words, all enterprises in Hong Kong should
follow the "rule of the games," and inland-financed enterprises
shall have no previliges and shall compete fairly and equally with
all other businesses there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
