<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldsters Now Outnumber Youngsters in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The number of people aged 65 or
older in Japan now exceeds for the first time the number of those
aged 14 or younger.
</P>
<P>
On June 1, the number of senior citizens was estimated at 19.54
million, about 15.5 percent of the total population, or about
50,000 more than the 19.49 million children, Japan's Management
and Coordination Agency said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Children under 14 make up 15.46 percent of Japan's population,
the agency said in its monthly population survey.
</P>
<P>
In June last year, there were 990,000 more children than senior
citizens. During the past year, the number of elderly people
increased by 730,000, while the number of children decreased by
310,000.
</P>
<P>
The reversal underlines the fact that Japan's population is
rapidly aging, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The "aging society" trend will continue, it predicted, adding
that by 2020, the number of older people was expected to rise to
22 percent of the total population.
</P>
<P>
In 2005, the proportion of the population aged at least 65 will
double the number aged 14 or younger, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Ties between Inland Area and Hong Kong to Be Further Enhanced after Handover: Official (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An Min said that Hong Kong's advantages, such as its role in
the global economy as an entrepot, cannot be replaced by any
inland city. Hong Kong will continue to serve as a showcase for
China's inland areas as well as a bridge linking China with other
parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
An said thatha stableof Hong Konis reinforceded by the
following three factors:
</P>
<P>
First, all of Hong Kong's current advantages, including its
ideal geographical position, well-facilitated harbor, close
relations with China's inland area, and broad-ranging economic
ties with other countries, will not change as a result of the
forthcoming handover;
</P>
<P>
Second, the Basic Law clearly stipulates that Hong Kong will
continue to keep both its free port status and liberal trade
policies after the handover, and the city enjoys high degree of
self autonomy in terms of executing powers of administration,
legislation and management in the economic areana, all of which has
provided legal protection for long-term stability and prosperity
in Hong Kong;
</P>
<P>
Third, the Beijing-Kowloon Railway which has become operational
lately will further extend Hong Kong's connections with the
central and northern provinces, thus bringing about closer trade
ties between these areas, and further enhancing Hong Kong's
position as an entrepot.
</P>
<P>
An noted that after the handover, trade between China's inland
areas and Hong Kong will be treated as one between a country and
its separate customs region, or regarded as a type of foreign
trade relations. And the economic and trade exchanges between the
two will follow international regulations and norms. As a separate
customs region, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region will
maintain and develop economic relations with other nations and
regions under the name of Hong Kong, China.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, An said, Moftec has worked out a set of basic
principles and policies regarding the economic and trade ties
between Hong Kong and China's inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The principles and policies stiputlate that the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region shall automatically determine and
execute trade control in accordance with the law; Hong Kongers who
invest in the inland shall enjoy the same treatment as foreign
investors; their permanent offfices established in the inland area
shall be managed in the same way as those owned by foreign
companies; international norms shall be applied to business
disputes that arise between Hong Kong and inland areas.
</P>
<P>
An said that the concerned departments plan to form a
coordinating system to handle economic and trade relations between
Hong Kong and the inland areas after the handover, so as to
facilitate the information exchange, policy adjustment, and
problem solving between the trade management departments of two
sides.
</P>
<P>
An said that the concerned departments have reached a consensus
on the basic principles and methods to be used by the the two
sides when dealing with trade statistics, protection of
intellectual property rights, and Hong Kong's participation in
multilateral international economic activities.
</P>
<P>
He said that the China's inland areas will give full support to
Hong Kong's efforts to implement effective market operation and
apply sound legal market system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
