<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's Population Growth Rate Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The growth rate of
Brazil's population dropped from 1.93 percent in 1991 to 1.3
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a census taken last year by the Brazilian
Institute of Geography and Statistics (Ibge), the population last
year was 156.8 million.
</P>
<P>
The reduction was mainly the result of a decease in the
reproduction rate of Brazilian women, which was down from 5.4
children per woman in 1965 to 2.7 in 1990, say Ibge experts.
</P>
<P>
The downward trend began at the end of the 1950s, when the
population in Brazil was growing at an average rate of 2.99
percent a year. It reduced to 2.89 percent in the 1960s and 2.48
percent in the 1970s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
