<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OSPAAAL Appeals for End to U.S. Embargo to Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Solidarity of
the Peoples of Africa, Asia, and Latin America (OSPAAAL) today
called on the international community to urge the United States to
end its economic, commercial and financial embargo against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
An OSPAAL document published in Havana said the embargo caused
indignation, made all the more profound by subsequent
modifications by the Helms-Burton Law.
</P>
<P>
The United States' Helms-Burton Act, of March 1996, allows
naturalized U.S. citizens to sue foreign firms or individuals
suspected of profiting from disputed properties in Cuba. It bars
executives of these companies from entering the United States.
</P>
<P>
The act sparked complaints from across the world, especially
the European Union (EU), which insisted the law was a violation of
the free trade principles of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The EU threatened to complain against the U.S. to the WTO
before the bloc reached agreement with the U.S. in April.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the EU suspended the complaint while the
Clinton administration promised to work with Congress to protect
European companies from the trade sanctions in the legislation.
</P>
<P>
The OSPAAAL warned that the Helms-Burton Act contradicts White
House' policy of defense of human rights.
</P>
<P>
The new anti-Cuban measures forecast bigger sanctions against
those who want to do business with the island. The law hardened
the embargo applied by the United States against Cuba since the
1960s, the OSPAAL said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
