<HEADLINE> Brazil to Test Fire Its First Satellite Launch Vehicle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Brazil will test fire its
first satellite launch vehicle -- a rocket booster -- next month,
senior space official Hugo Pereria Chaves said.
</P>
<P>
Chaves, director of the Aeronautics and Space Institute, said
the Alcantara launch center in the northeastern state of Maranhao
will begin countdown for the blast-off on July 2.
</P>
<P>
Tests to be carried out during the countdown and their results
will be decisive for the scheduled final launch, the official was
quoted as saying by media reports published here today.
</P>
<P>
The rocket, capable of lifting payloads of 100 to 350 kilograms
into orbits 250 to 1,000 kilometers above the earth, will be used
to deploy data-gathering remote sensing satellites.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, believed to be the only space-faring nation in Latin
America, has launched several satellites over past years by using
rockets or launch services provided by other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
