<HEADLINE> Thailand, U.S. Sign Deal to Build Nuclear Reactor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Office of Atomic Energy
for Peace (OAEP) Thursday concluded a contract with a U.S. company
to build the country's first nuclear reactor.
</P>
<P>
The 3.3-billion-baht (132 million U.S. dollars) deal was made
by the OAEP with the General Atomic Corporation after months of
delay due to concerns over safety, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
However, the OAEP insisted that the construction of the reactor
will begin only after Thailand secures a safety analysis report
for the project from the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission or a
neutral international nuclear institute.
</P>
<P>
The 10-megawatt nuclear reactor reportedly will be installed in
Nakhon Mayok Province's Ongkharak Nuclear Research Center to
produce radioactive isotopes for research, medical and food
preservation purposes.
</P>
<P>
A nuclear waste treatment facility would also be built in the
area.
</P>
<P>
The design of the whole project will cover a period of two
years under the contract.  
</P>
</TEXT>
