<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government Foresees Investment Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
foreseen a drop in state-approved foreign investment for the 1997
calendar year from the 1996 figure of 29.9 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is going to fall, but I don't really know the
reason. I am still looking at it," Investment Minister Sanyoto
Sastrowardoyo said here Thursday, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government announced earlier this month that it had
approved foreign investment proposals amounting to 14.4 billion
dollars in the first five months of the year, a decline of 25.5
percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The minister described as "not a major concern" the fall which
he said was due to the country's general elections held last
month.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 approved foreign investment figure was already down
from 39.9 billion dollars in 1995.  
