<HEADLINE> 36 Percent of Chinese Urban Families May Buy Cars in Three Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Some 36 percent of Chinese urban
families might buy cars in three years, the Ministry of Civil
Affairs said today.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey conducted by the ministry early this
year, 64 percent of these families will choose to buy Chinese-made
cars, most of which are manufactured at foreign-funded plants.
</P>
<P>
As for imported cars, the majority of the respondents said that
the Korean-made Dawoo is the most popular model on the Chinese
market.
</P>
<P>
The survey targeted 4,600 citizens in 31 major cities,
representing a total population of 350 million.
</P>
<P>
For Chinese, the most well-known imported car is the Mercedes
Benz, the survey shows. When asked what brands they prefer to buy,
the respondents said their first choice is the Jetta -- the
Chinese version of the German-made Volkswagen. Other favorites
include the Sino-German made Santana, the Sino-French Fukang,
Dawoo, the Sino-US made Cherokee, and the Red Flag.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that the first factor Chinese consider when
buying a car is the price, followed by its safety and follow-up
services provided by the dealer.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe there will be some 1.3 to 1.5 million cars
owned by Chinese families by the end of the century. More cars
will be bought by ordinary citizens than for government use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
