<HEADLINE> Indonesian President: No Ties With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
stressed that his country will never establish diplomatic
relations with Israel unless a just and lasting solution has been
found to the Arab-Israel conflict.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia is concerned about the deadlock in the Middle East
peace process," the president said at a banquet last night in
honor of Syrian Prime Minister Mahmoud Al-Zoubi, who arrived here
on Thursday for a five-day state visit to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto said his country is concerned because the Israeli
government has still not carried out the various U.N. resolutions
on the conflict nor the land-for-peace principle agreed upon by
all sides during the Madrid conference in 1991.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli occupation of Arab territories is obviously
illegal and constitutes a new form of colonialism and racialism
which are against our constitution," Soeharto said.
</P>
<P>
He urged Israel to return occupied Arab territories such as
Syria's Golan Heights, southern Lebanon, Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations, the president said geographically Syria
and Indonesia are situated far away from each other, "but Syria is
not alien to Indonesia. In 1947, Syria was the third country to
recognize Indonesia's independence and sovereignty," Soeharto
noted.
</P>
<P>
Official sources here said Soeharto and the Syrian prime
minister will hold a 90-minute meeting this morning and then they
will witness the signing of a number of accords between the two
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
