<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Worries About Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto has
expressed concern over the great number of teenagers addicted to
opium despite the government's efforts to keep them from drug
abuse.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt that drug abuse can threaten the existence
of nations, human beings and cultures," the president said
Thursday in his written address on the U.N. resolution declaring
June 26 as the world anti-drug day.
</P>
<P>
Official sources today quoted the president as saying the
government has taken various measures to check drug abuse but the
problem remains.
</P>
<P>
"No nation is currently free from the abuse of these dangerous
drugs. The syndicate of drug trafficking is growing and moving
smartly in all aspects of life," he said, adding that many drug
traffickers have actually been seized and got severe punishment
but the activities continued.
</P>
<P>
"The government is very concerned about the misuse of opium. We
have signed the U.N. convention on the eradication of illegal
psychotropic and narcotic trafficking. We have also have narcotic
and psychotropic laws," he added.  
</P>
