<HEADLINE> China Wants World to Know of Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Culture
announced here today that the country has launched a high-profile
publicity blitz to inform the whole world that China resumes its
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 Chinese embassies and consulates in different
countries have been sponsoring films and photo exhibitions about
the event. By early July, some 600 film will have been shown
worldwide, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a number of foreign TV networks will broadcast
programs on the Hong Kong theme, featuring Chinese reporters and
foreign diplomats.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has prepared more than 1,000 videotapes translated
into a dozen foreign languages, as well as 40,000 educational
materials which will be distributed overseas.
</P>
<P>
The hottest ticket is for the "Opium War," the most expensive
film in Chinese movie-making history. The movie has been
translated into foreign languages and released overseas, the
ministry added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Chinese media have been broadcasting and printing
hundreds of stories in different languages on the return of Hong
Kong. 
</P>
