<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Nations to Obey Official Ceiling on Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- OPEC member nations have promised
to maintain the current official oil production ceiling of 25.03
million barrels a day in the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
A communique released here today after a ministerial meeting of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) said all
of its 11 members agreed to abide by their individual quotas.
</P>
<P>
OPEC Secretary-General Rilwanu Lukman said he was confident
that efforts will be made to rein in production.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, some member nations were criticized for their
overproduction. Experts estimated that OPEC's real daily output is
around 27 million barrels, 2 million above its official ceiling.
</P>
<P>
Since early this year, average oil price on the world market
has dropped from 25 U.S. dollars a barrel to the present level of
about 18 dollars a barrel, well below OPEC's target of 21 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Due to sufficient oil reserves in Europe and the competition of
non-OPEC nations, the group's members have no better way to
stabilize oil prices except the strict control of overproduction.
</P>
<P>
Also at the meeting, Qatar's Energy and Industry Minister
Abdullah Bin Hamad Al-Attiya was chosen as OPEC's president for
the next six months to replace Libyan Energy Minister Abdalla
Salem El-Badri.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC meeting opened here Wednesday and ended today. The
next meeting will be in Jakarta, Capital of Indonesia, in November.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members are Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Libya,
Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates and Venezuela.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin America to Invest More in Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Latin American and Caribbean
countries will invest some 23 billion U.S. dollars in the next 13
years to boost their power output, a senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
The official, with the Latin American Organization of Energy,
made the remark when coordinating here a project aimed to change
consumption habits and apply energy conservation technologies.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica, Nicaragua and El Salvador were the first to take
part in the three-year project starting this week with the
co-sponsorship of the regional energy group and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Experience gained in these countries will be extended to
Panama, Guatemala and Honduras later on, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The Latin American Organization of Energy has a mandate to
bring together 25 countries in the region for the protection,
commercialization and rational use of energy resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
