<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Foreign Reserves Drop in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's foreign reserves were
posted at 33.3 billion U.S. dollars in May this year, down 4
billion dollars from April, according to the Bank of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the figure, made public along with other economic
indicators by the central bank today, was better than expected.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, it was widely anticipated that the country's foreign
reserves would fall to around 30 billion dollars in May from 37.3
billion dollars in April, as the central bank spent heavily to
defend the baht from attacks by currency speculators.
</P>
<P>
Some company managers said the 33.3 billion dollars in foreign
reserves would mean that the central bank's position is still
strong and can effectively cope with any further attacks on the
currency.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's foreign reserves were at 38.1 billion dollars in
March this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
