<HEADLINE> Drug Business Pollutes Tributaries of Amazon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Cocaine production and
refinement in Peru, Colombia and Bolivia are polluting tributaries
of the Amazon River, a United Nations official said today.
</P>
<P>
Over 20 million liters of chemicals used by drug refineries are
flushed into rivers, said Aldo Lale Demoz, director of the Latin
American and Caribbean program for international drug control.
</P>
<P>
The damage would be soon visible in Brazil, the U.N. official
warned. The Amazon, rising in the Andes mountain range, is the
most important river in Brazil. 
</P>
