<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Ties between Inland Area and Hong Kong to be Further Enhanced after Handover: Official (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- After the July 1 handover of Hong
Kong, trade cooperation between China's inland area and Hong Kong
can be extended to "wider fields" within the framework of one
country, said a senior official with China's Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation (Moftec).
</P>
<P>
An Min, assistant minister of Moftec, told Xinhua in a recent
interview that retaining Hong Kong's current kingpin status in the
international trade arena after the handover is in the best
interests of both the motherland and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"The central government has thus far determined that the
mainstay of its trade policy regarding Hong Kong is maintaining
and enhancing Hong Kong's stance as an international trading,
finance, navigation and information center," he noted.
</P>
<P>
An said that China's opening-up drive in the early 1980s
started a new chapter of trade cooperation between the inland area
and Hong Kong, which are now not only partners in trade but also
in investment and other forms of economic exchange, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the General Administration of
Customs, the total trade volume between the inland area and Hong
Kong last year hit 40.7 billion US dollars, or 15 times the amount
in 1978. Hong Kong is now the biggest export destination and third
biggest trade partner of the inland area.
</P>
<P>
"The trade volume between the inland area and Hong Kong in the
first four months of this year topped 14.1 billion dollars,
keeping its upward trend," An added.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Hong Kong is the main source of inflowing capital
to the inland area. Between 1979 and 1996, Hong Kong investors
registered a total 160,000 projects in the inland, with an
aggregate contractual investment of 260 billion dollars. Of this
amount, some 99 billion dollars have been used.
</P>
<P>
Projects involving Hong Kong financing and those with
actually-used Hong Kong investment accounted for more than 60
percent of the total in the inland area. "In the first quarter of
this year, an additional 1,720 Hong Kong-funded projects were
registered in the inland area and some 3.593 billion dollars from
Hong Kong investors had been used," An said.
</P>
<P>
An said that the compatibility of the economies in the inland
area and Hong Kong helped to form the mutually-beneficial trade
ties. "After the handover, the trade links will become more
direct, convenient and closer than ever," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Promises Action on Earth Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- United States President
Bill Clinton told the United Nations Earth Summit today that his
country would take action to deal with climate change, and would
advance sustainable development at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said his country would provide one billion U.S. dollars
in assistance over the next five years to help developing
countries reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
The fund would go to programs that support energy efficiency,
develop alternative energy sources and improve resources
management to promote growth that does not adversely affect the
climate.
</P>
<P>
The president said the U.S. would continue to encourage private
investment that meets environmental standards. The U.S. Overseas
Private Investment Corporation would now require its projects to
adhere to new and strengthened environmental guidelines.
</P>
<P>
At home, Clinton said, the U.S. must unleash more of the
creative power of its people to meet the challenge of climate
change.
</P>
<P>
The United States was working with its auto industry to produce
cars by early next century that would be three times as fuel
efficient as today's models.
</P>
<P>
It would also work with businesses and communities to install
solar panels on one million roofs around the country by 2010 to
help reduce the earth's temperature.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been under attacks at the summit for
refusing to set targets to cut global warming, and for reducing
funds for ecological projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Power Consumption Up in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Italy's electricity consumption
nationwide in May was up 2.9 percent against the previous month, a
sign that the country's manufacturing activities are picking up.
</P>
<P>
The power consumption of 22.2 billion kilowatt-hours last
month, said the national electricity authority known as ENEL, was
a 4.0 percent increase compared with the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
While making the latest statistics public today, the government
bureau said the 4.0 percent rise actually took place in a month
that had less work days than the same calendar month of 1996.
</P>
<P>
In May, ENEL facilities boosted power generation by 3.0 percent
over the same month last year to 18.7 billion kilowatt-hours, and
1.0 percent more electricity was imported to satisfy the needs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
