<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marked Improvement in Shanghai's Infrastructural Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The municipal government of
China's economic powerhouse of Shanghai has placed development of
infrastructural facilities at the top of the agenda, and has
reported remarkable improvements in the public utilities, the
urban traffic network and afforestation programs.
</P>
<P>
Local statistics show that the city spent a total of 37.878
billion yuan in 1996 on the construction of infrastructural
facilities, mainly involving power, communications and
telecommunications, transport, public utilities, environmental
protection and afforestation.
</P>
<P>
To date, the city has developed a daily coal gas production
capacity of 8.48 million cu m, which covers 90 percent of the
local households, and running water production capacity of 8.8
million tons.
</P>
<P>
The city also has a well-developed urban traffic network of
buses, subways and taxis.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's green space has extended to more than 7,200 ha, with
average per capita green space increasing to 1.92 sq m. So far,
some 17 percent of the city's urban areas has been afforested.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city has improved its daily sewage treatment
capacity to 1.893 million tons, representing a 2.8-fold increase
over the previous year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
