<HEADLINE> American Olympic Kayaker Drowns in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Washington, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Two-time Olympic kayaker
Richard Weiss was drowned in an accident on the White Salmon River
on Wednesday, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
Weiss, who finished sixth in the slalom in the Atlanta Games
and 16th at Barcelona, failed to surface Wednesday after he went
over a 15-foot waterfall in the river, south of the town of Trout
Lake.
</P>
<P>
A friend who was kayaking with Weiss tried to find him in the
water, then went for help. A kayak team statement said Weiss was
wearing a life jacket and helmet.
</P>
<P>
Weiss moved to nearby Hood River, Oregon after the 1996
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Originally from Steamboat Springs, Colorado, Weiss, 33, and his
wife Rosi were expecting their first child this fall.
</P>
<P>
The White Salmon is a popular river for kayaking and was
running high because of the spring runoff.
</P>
<P>
Weiss won the slalom Olympic trials last year and was selected
the kayak team's slalom male athlete of the year.
</P>
<P>
He became the first American to medal in men's kayak at a world
championship when he won the silver medal in 1993 in Italy. He was
third overall in the World Cup standings in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
