<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: NZ Budget Triggers Debate on Priority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Delivering the government
budget each year is a usual business in New Zealand. What makes it
different this year is that the budget was not announced by the
finance minister as in the past, but by the new treasurer, a post
created after the National Party and the New Zealand First party
formed the country's first coalition government late last year.
</P>
<P>
Not only the person who delivered the budget changed, but the
focus of the financial document also shifted. The past National
government put emphasis on increasing budget surplus and paying
off government debt. This year, the budget lays stress on boosting
government spending instead, in the fields of health, education
and social welfare in particular.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the budget in the parliament yesterday, Treasurer
Winston Peters said the budget "shows our commitment to delivering
on the Coalition Agreement promises in health, education,
employment, safer communities, the environment, saving for
retirement and to older New Zealanders."
</P>
<P>
But the cost to keep the promises is an extra spending of 5
billion NZ dollars (3.4 billion U.S. dollars) in the coming three
years and falling government surplus, which has been on the rise
in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The budget reported a surplus of 2.4 billion dollars for the
1996/97 year. But the surplus is projected to slip to 1.5 billion
dollars in the coming year and will not recover to the present
level until 1999/2000.
</P>
<P>
The budget seems to contain little to inspire the business
circles, whose confidence has been on the decline since the
formation of the coalition government alongside a slowdown in
economic growth. Business people fear that increased spending on
social welfare, health and education will weaken the government's
financial position and bring about a negative impact on the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Describing his budget as "conservative" and "prudent," Peters
tried to allay the concern of the business people by stating that
the government's intention is to stay within the 5 billion dollar
spending limit.
</P>
<P>
The budget has satisfied none of the opposition parties.
Despite more money for health and education, the Labor Party said
the budget "has ignored the wider challenges in the health and
education sectors."
</P>
<P>
The ACT party has criticized the government from the other end,
saying "New Zealand needs a tax cut now." It argues that canceling
tax cuts last year destroyed consumer confidence and so undermined
job growth and caused the present economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
However, Peters maintains his optimism. He predicted that the
economic growth will rebound toward the end of this year and
strengthen in 1998/99. In the year to March 1999, the economy
will grow 4.2 percent, he said in the budget.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Argentine Minister of Justice Appointed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem today appointed Raul Granillo Ocampo as the country's new
minister of justice to replace Elias Jassan who resigned recently
because of his alleged links with the "Yabran" case.
</P>
<P>
Granillo was the country's ambassador to the United States
before accepting this post.
</P>
<P>
Alfredo Yabran, a well known entrepreneur, is allegedly
involved in the slaying of photographer and newsman Jose Luis
Cabezas who reportedly made incriminating photos for an article on
a gang of organized crime leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
