<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A-maizing Black Corn Arrives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Two new varieties of black maize,
which were named "Black Pearl" and "Black Guanyin," have been
successfully bred by a Chinese amateur agro-technician in the city
of Liaoyang, Liaoning Province, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
After 10 years of effort, Wang Litian -- a traditional Chinese
painter -- fostered the two variations of maize or corn through
the method of hybridization.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar held by the China Land Economy Research Society
(CLERS) on Wednesday, several agricultural professors and
economists in Beijing said the two kinds of black maize, with
better taste and nutritive value than the traditional ear of corn,
will suffice to meet the demands of most people.
</P>
<P>
In addition to niacin and several trace elements such as
calcium, iron and selenium, the two kinds of black maize contain
0.373 grams of lysine per 100 grams, which is 0.123 grams more
than ordinary yellow corn, according to a report by the Nutrition
and Food Hygiene Research Institute of the Chinese Academy of
Preventive Medicine.
</P>
<P>
The development of agriculture in some poor and remote areas
should rely on high-quality and improved breeds of crops in
accordance with the market-oriented economy, said Du Runsheng,
former director of the Research Center of Rural Development of the
State Council.
</P>
<P>
The two kinds of valuable maize can help farmers in remote
regions of north China and northeast China to extricate themselves
from poverty and promote the development of local rural economies,
said Lin Jingyao, deputy director of the Environment and
Development Committee of the CLERS.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0251 </DOCNO>
