<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coal-port Construction Ends Fourth Phase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Yesterday was a red-letter day for
Qinhuangdao port: the fourth phase of its coal terminal was
announced to have been officially completed and its was expected
to go into trial operation on July 1, according to today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
The wharf has been connected with Datong-Qinhuangdao Multiple
Railway to speed up coal transportation from Shanxi and Shaanxi
provinces and the western area of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region, said Nie Zhenyi, director of the Qinhuangdao Port
Authority.
</P>
<P>
"It will help provide enough energy for east and south China to
back up their rapid economic growth," Nie said.
</P>
<P>
The fourth phase of Qinhuangdao coal wharf includes two
35,000-dwt berths and one 100,000-dwt berth. It is expected to
handle 30 million tons of coal annually, and 40 million tons are
awaited after further extension.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has invested 848 million yuan in the
project since 1993 when its construction was kicked off.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Japanese government offered 10.3 billion yen
(91.2 million US dollars) in loans for the project.
</P>
<P>
The help protect the environment, 1.9 million yuan has been
invested in the project to import advanced facilities from
developed countries to help decrease pollution, Nie said.
</P>
<P>
So far, Qinhuangdao port boasts 41 berths, of which 26 are
deep-water ones for ships over 10,000 dwt. It has set up constant
trading and shipping relations with ports in more than 80
countries and regions in the world.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the volume of freight handled in the port reached 83
million tons, ranking it second in the country.
</P>
<P>
The port handled 65 million tons of coal in 1996, marking it as
the largest coal-loading port in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
