<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Kills 33 in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 26 (Xinhua) -- High temperatures in Mexico's
northern states have caused the death of at least 33 persons so
far this summer, according to official counts available today.
</P>
<P>
The highest temperatures registered by now -- 44.6 and 43.6
degrees centigrade -- are those of El Organo and El Altar areas in
the state of Sonora, the National Commission of Water reported.
</P>
<P>
The dry and very hot air in the country's northeast, north and
southeast was caused by high pressure systems on the Pacific Ocean
and the Gulf of Mexico, said the National Meteorological Service.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture, Livestock and Rural Development Minister Francisco
Labastida Ochoa said his ministry is ready to give more support to
farmers trying to solve problems caused by the high temperatures.
</P>
<P>
To prevent dehydration, residents in the affected areas have
been instructed to give food and drinks to children under five,
who are known to be the most vulnerable to the heat, said Ochoa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
