<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Small Business Minister Geoff Prosser admitted yesterday to
having had more than 100 meetings or conversations regarding his
private businesses since becoming a minister, but continues to
survive Opposition attempts to have him dismissed. The minister
faces what has become a plethora of conflict of interest
allegations.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Australia's 375 million U.S. dollar annual car exports to
New Zealand have been threatened by a budget announcement in
Wellington of "swift removal" of tariffs on non-Australian
imports. Australia enjoys tariff-free entry into New Zealand under
the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- The federal Health Department is investigating a medical
trial conducted on more than 160 Victorian girls to try to stop
them growing tall. The girls were given a sex hormone, later
linked to vaginal cancer, because researchers said they wanted to
give them a better chance of finding boyfriends or becoming
ballerinas.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard will adopt a new tactic in his
battle against uniform greenhouse gas reduction targets in his
meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington today.
</P>
</TEXT>
