<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade, Banking See Bright Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Bright prospects for foreign trade
development and a more open financial sector in China are
anticipated by senior Chinese officials, today's "China Daily"
reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based newspaper quotes Sun Zhenyu, vice-minister
of Foreign Trade and Economic Co-operation as saying that on the
basis of sharp tariff cuts last year, China will make greater
efforts to bring the general level of its tariff rate to 15
percent by 2000, further reducing non-tariff measures, and open
its service trade market.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that in 2000, China's imports and exports will
total 400 billion US dollars, indicating that in the coming four
years, China will provide the world with a market of nearly 700
billion US dollars and with trade opportunities worth 1,400
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, actual overseas investment in China had hit
over 177 billion US dollars and over 140,000 overseas-funded
ventures had gone into operation.
</P>
<P>
Foreign financial institutions in China will gradually be
granted national status treatment instead of the low tax rate
preferential treatment.
</P>
<P>
At present foreign financial institutions, both in number and
business scope, have become an important part of China's financial
system, the paper says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
