<HEADLINE> Annan to Open UN-Sponsored Cyprus Talks Near New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan will open the forthcoming talks of
the leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities near New
York, U.N. officials said today.
</P>
<P>
After the opening session, Annan will hand over the presidency
of the talks to his special adviser for Cyprus, Diego Cordovez, a
former Ecuadorean foreign minister, according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides, who
heads the Greek Cypriot community, and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash will be held at a resort and conference center called
Troutbeck, about 90 miles north of New York.
</P>
<P>
Norway will pick up the bill for the U.N.-sponsored talks
scheduled for July 9-13, a member of the Norwegian mission to the
United Nations said.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the encounter between Clerides and Denktash is
expected to be between 30,000 and 40,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Norway also provided facilities for ground-breaking talks in
Oslo in 1993 between Israel and the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy to contribute to an effort by the
secretary-general to get talks going between the two parties on
Cyprus," the Norwegian official told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
