<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Says It Finds No Laser on Russian Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States today said an
investigation had failed to confirm its suspicion that a Russian
ship fired laser at a Canadian helicopter off the U.S. coast,
injuring a U.S. Navy lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
"There is no physical evidence tying the eye injury of the
American officer to a laser located on the Russian merchant
vessel," said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
He said no laser had been found, but insisted again that the
temporary eye injuries were "consistent with injuries that would
be expected from exposure to a low-level laser, such as a laser
range-finder for example."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. said in May that the Russian fishing ship Kapitan Man
may have illuminated the Canadian military helicopter with a laser
in Puget Sound, off the State of Washington.
</P>
<P>
Defense officials said privately last month that the Russian
ship was suspected of spying on U.S. submarines and that the
CH-124 Canadian Maritime Pacific Command helicopter was taking
photographs of the ship in daylight.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government and the ship's captain denied that
a laser was used, and a U.S. Coast Guard search of the Kapitan
Man at Tacoma, Washington, three days after the incident found
no laser device aboard.
</P>
<P>
"We found actually no suggestion that there had been a laser on
board the ship or that the source of the laser, if a laser caused
these injuries, no suggestion that the laser emanated from that
ship," Bacon told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Experts Urge Clinton to Stop NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Forty-six U.S. foreign policy
experts and former officials today urged President Bill Clinton to
stop expanding the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
In an open letter to Clinton, the group said that NATO
expansion would delay approval of arms-control treaties with
Russia, divide Europe and reduce NATO's military effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
Among signatories of the letter are Sam Nunn, ex-chairman of
the Senate Armed Services Committee; two recent ambassadors to the
Soviet Union, Jack Matlock and Arthur Hartman, and former Central
Intelligence Agency Director Stansfield Turner.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from the 16-member NATO will meet in the Spanish
capital of Madrid on July 8-9 to discuss plans to expand the
16-member alliance into Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
On June 12, Clinton announced U.S. support for Poland, Hungary
and the Czech Republic to join the alliance, and invitations are
expected to be issued at the Madrid summit.
</P>
<P>
The European members of NATO also expressed their support for
Romania and Slovenia to join.
</P>
<P>
"The current U.S.-led effort to expand NATO is a policy error
of historic proportions," said the anti-expansion letter,
stressing that NATO has no reason to move quickly.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that NATO expansion will decrease allied security
and unsettle European stability," said the letter. "We believe
that NATO expansion is neither necessary nor desirable, and this
ill-conceived policy can and should be put on hold."
</P>
<P>
The letter proposed promoting membership in the European Union
for the countries of Central and Eastern Europe, developing NATO's
Partnership for Peace program and concentrating on nuclear weapons
reduction, which it called the main threat to U.S. security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970627.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mackey to Lead 2nd Oklahoma Bombing Trial Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Larry Mackey, the prosecutor
who was instrumental in persuading a federal jury to sentence
Timothy McVeigh to death, will lead the prosecution team for the
second Oklahoma City bombing suspect, Terry Nichols.
</P>
<P>
Mackey, 46, has been a federal prosecutor since 1980.
</P>
<P>
McVeigh was condemned earlier this month on conviction of
murder and conspiracy in the April 19, 1995 Oklahoma bombing that
killed 168.
</P>
<P>
Nichols, 41, faces murder and conspiracy charges and is
expected to be tried this year, although no date has been set.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Janet Reno called Mackey an "experienced trial
lawyer" and an "accomplished leader" today in announcing Mackey's
appointment.
</P>
<P>
Mackey was deputy prosecutor in the McVeigh trial. In addition
to the closing argument, he helped lead prosecutor Joseph Hartzler
with trial strategy, jury selection, witness questioning and case
management.
</P>
<P>
Hartzler announced long before the McVeigh trial that he would
handle no other trials connected with the bombing. He has returned
to his job as an assistant U.S. attorney in Springfield, Illinois.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
